<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Challenges Online Companies  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GALVIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Assessing the future of the Internet,
President Clinton challenged online companies Friday to strengthen
consumer privacy safeguards and ordered government agencies to
evaluate the security of their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged the high-tech industry to work with him to ensure
that every America, regardless of class, has access to the tools
they need in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are two (areas) which are absolutely vital to keep the
information economy and all America growing strong,'' the president
said. ''The first is Internet security and privacy and the second
is closing the digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at an Aspen Institute forum Friday in the heart of
Silicon Valley at the start of a two-day visit with political
overtones to California. He helped raise money for Democrats such
as Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., whom he promoted as a possible
running mate for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she is immensely talented and would be good at
anything,'' Clinton said. ''But this is a decision that the vice
president should make after he wins the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days before Super Tuesday's primary elections, he also was
raising $1.6 million for Democrats and drawing sharp differences
between his party and Republican candidates on gun control and
patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The president issued an executive memorandum directing federal
agencies to ensure that their systems won't be used in the kinds of
''denial of service'' attacks that shut down several high-profile
Web sites last month.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking the day after the nation's largest Internet advertising
company backed away from a controversial plan to build extensive
personal profiles of Web users, Clinton challenged industry leaders
to do more to protect privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys have shown that privacy is a major reason why more
consumers don't shop online. The president applauded the fact that
the number of firms with privacy policies increased from 15 percent
to 65 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the American people know it's still not enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some subjects are so sensitive I believe they should have
legal protection,'' Clinton said. ''Our medical records, our legal
records, our financial records, any interaction we have with our
children online.''
</P>
<P>
   The president told the industry leaders and educators attending
a forum on communications and society that fair practices include
notifying consumers what information is collected and how it will
be used; the option to choose whether information can be shared
with third parties; access to information a site has collected;
security of that information during transmission and storage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also renewed a pledge to cooperate with industry to
bridge the ''digital divide'' between the rich and poor and urged
the players in the industry to consider the impact of a
''tax-free'' Internet would have on local and state budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most online transactions are free from sales tax. But
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers last week called for
establishing sales taxes for online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast visit gave the president a chance to dabble in
politics just days before California -- the largest electoral state
-- votes chooses Republican and Democrat nominees to succeed him on
Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Clinton was attending two events to raise
$600,000 for the re-election of Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
and the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, as well as a
$400,000 Democratic National Committee Dinner. Clinton was the
featured guest Saturday at two DNC events in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The president also was holding a private meeting in San
Francisco with leaders the clergy, who often play a key role in
getting Democrats to the voting booths on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president would use the
fund-raising speeches to draw stark contrasts between the
Democratic candidates and the Republican candidates on the issues
of gun control and a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton travels to Alabama to participate in the 35th
anniversary of the civil rights march on Selma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0016 </TRAILER>
