<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flames 4, Mighty Ducks 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- Jarome Iginla extended his point-scoring
streak to 15 games with two goals Friday night as the Calgary
Flames defeated the Anaheim Mighty Ducks 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Iginla has 12 goals and 13 assists during the streak, which ties
him with Luc Robitaille, Jaromir Jagr, Pierre Turgeon and Patrik
Elias for the longest streak in the NHL this season. Robitaille's
streak is still going.
</P>
<P>
   Iginla opened the scoring 6:04 into the game and made it 4-0
just 42 seconds into the third period with his 23rd goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Valeri Bure, with his 34th goal, and Jeff Cowan, with his first,
also scored for Calgary, winners of three in a row and 5-1-1 in its
last seven.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Savard had an assist on Iginla's goal to extend his points
streak to nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Miller's power-play goal at 7:17 of the third period ended
goaltender Fred Brathwaite's bid for a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary moved within one point of idle Colorado and San Jose,
who are tied for seventh in the Western Conference. Calgary has a
game in hand on both.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary outshot Anaheim 37-17.
</P>
<P>
   Bure made it 2-0 at 8:31 of the second period when he collected
his own rebound off a backhander and flipped a forehand over goalie
Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Cowan gave Calgary a three-goal lead from a bad angle,
deflecting in Jason Wiemer's centering pass.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburgh replaced Hebert with Dominic
Roussel after Iginla's third-period goal and Roussel stopped all
eight shots he faced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
