<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman to endorse Bush in Connecticut, not New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman, who said earlier
this week she will formally endorse Texas Gov. George W. Bush prior
to the New York primary, will do just that on Saturday -- in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is slated to endorse Bush at a news conference with
the candidate and Connecticut Gov. John Rowland Saturday night at
Bradley International Airport in Windsor Locks, Conn. New York and
Connecticut are among the states holding primaries on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman on Monday told reporters attending the National
Governors Association meeting in Washington that she would ''do
something in New York'' for Bush as part of the Republican
governors' effort to support him in his bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   However, the moderate Whitman won't make the endorsement in New
York because of a scheduling conflict, according to spokesman Peter
McDonough. McDonough said Bush was campaigning in the southern tier
region of upstate New York, and ''she couldn't get to Binghamton.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has long said she intends to formally endorse Bush, but
that she was waiting for the right time to help make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman wants to lend some moderate credentials to Bush, who
came under fire for appearing at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina in an attempt to woo conservatives. Bush has subsequently
apologized for not speaking out against ''anti-Catholic sentiments
and racial prejudice,'' while at the university, which bans
interracial dating and whose leaders have labeled the Catholic
church a ''Satanic cult.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonough said the endorsement by Whitman will show Bush has
''fiscal conservatives and social moderates'' in his camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 0023 </TRAILER>
