<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Hits Papua New Guinea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- A powerful earthquake struck Papua New Guinea
early Saturday, shortly before another tremor struck the Banda Sea
near East Timor, seismologists in Hong Kong and Australia said.
</P>
<P>
   The first tremor, with a magnitude estimated at 6.4, struck near
the Fly River, about 190 miles west of the capital Port Moresby,
said Mark Leonard, a spokesman for the Australian Geological Survey
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of damages or casualties, he
said, or evidence that there had been a tsunami -- an earthquake
generated wave.
</P>
<P>
   The area was not heavily built up and the small, wooden
buildings common in the region are very resilient in earthquakes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A separate quake with an estimated magnitude of 6.4 hit the
Banda Sea, west of Papua New Guinea and north of Western Australia,
the Hong Kong Observatory said.
</P>
<P>
   It was centered beneath the sea about 230 miles east-northeast
of Dili, East Timor, the observatory said. There were no reports of
damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, a series of tsunamis killed an estimated 2,000
people in northern Papua New Guinea's Sepik Province.
</P>
<P>
   An earthquake with a magnitude of more than 6.0 can cause
considerable damage when centered under heavily populated areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
