<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bob Jones Univ. Drops Race Date Ban
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Bob Jones University will drop its ban on interracial
dating, Bob Jones III said on CNN's ''Larry King Live'' Friday night. ''As of
today, right now, we're dropping it,'' Jones III said. Criticism followed after
Republican Presidential Candidate George W. Bush visited the school last month.
The ban on interracial dating was just one criticism Bush faced after his visit
to the Greenville school. Bush apologized earlier this week for failing to
criticize the anti-Catholic views of the university when he visited last month.
During his appearance there, the Texas governor told his audience that he shared
their values.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haiti Postpones Elections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Dogged by organizational problems that left
more than 1 million voters unregistered, Haiti on Friday postponed March 19
elections, without specifying a new date. The announcement came only hours after
the U.N. Security Council urged Haiti to stick ''as closely as possible'' to its
schedule for elections, which it said were crucial to the Caribbean nation's
fledgling democracy. ''A new electoral timetable for the balloting will be
published as soon as possible,'' said electoral council spokesman Roland
Sainristil. He cited ''innumerable difficulties surrounding voter
registration.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Floodwaters Drop, Freeing Thousands
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHIBUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- The water level in the flooded Limpopo River
valley dropped unexpectedly Friday, freeing thousands of people who were
marooned for days in trees and on rooftops during Mozambique's worst flooding on
record. Rescuers have saved more than 12,000 people from the floodwaters. But
tragedy struck the rescue effort when a boat capsized, drowning four children.
And in refugee camps, many people went hungry for yet another day. Officials
expect the floods' death toll to run into the thousands, and the collection of
corpses has been hampered by a shortage of body bags.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Slain Michigan Girl Mourned
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- At a memorial service Friday night, some 1,000 mourners
grieved for Kayla Rolland, the 6-year-old girl who was shot to death in her
elementary school, allegedly by a 6-year-old classmate. Kayla, in a red dress,
lay in an open casket, a small doll of the TV character Barney beneath it. In
her hands was a small card with a poem titled ''I'm free.'' The boy who shot
Kayla has told police that it was an accident and that he meant only to scare
her. The two are believed to have scuffled on the playground the day before. No
charges are expected against the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chile Gives Pinochet a Hero's Welcome
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet, 84, returned home a free man
and was greeted by thousands of cheering supporters after 16 months of detention
in Britain. Opponents, however, vowed to prosecute him at home for the abuses of
his 17-year regime. An official government report says 3,197 people died or
disappeared at the hands of Pinochet's secret police after he toppled the
elected Marxist president in a 1973 coup. Pinochet was arrested in London on
Oct. 16, 1998, on a warrant issued by a Spanish judge. Britain considered
extraditing him to Spain and then set him free, saying he was too ill for trial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA: Gene Therapy Rules Violated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration accused a University of
Pennsylvania researcher Friday of violating safety regulations in a gene therapy
experiment in which a patient died. In a stern warning letter, the FDA said that
Dr. James M. Wilson of the University of Pennsylvania ''violated regulations
governing the proper conduct of clinical studies'' in a series of gene therapy
experiments designed to correct a liver disease. Wilson headed a gene therapy
experimental study that was halted after the death of 18-year-old Jesse
Gelsinger of Tucson, Ariz. The teen-ager is the first patient known to have died
as a direct result of a gene therapy experiment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 202.28; Nasdaq Up 160.28
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks climbed higher Friday after government data showed
some easing of the tight labor market. The Dow Jones industrial average rose
202.28 points to close at 10,367.20. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,715-1,271. For the week, the blue-chip index rose 505.08 points, its best
performance since July. The Nasdaq composite index rose 160.28 to 4,914.79,
another record high.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuggets Beat Warriors 122-88
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Keon Clark set career highs with 29 points and 16 rebounds as
Denver's reserves led the Nuggets to a 122-88 win over the Golden State Warriors
Friday night. Clark was 13-for-20 from the field. Chris Gatling added 18 points
and nine rebounds and the Nuggets backups outscored Golden State's 73-38.
Vonteego Cummings had a career-high 19 points for the Warriors, who lost to the
Nuggets for the first time in three games.
</P>
