<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers 107, Pacers 92  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal had 31 points and 15
rebounds Friday night as the Los Angeles Lakers didn't let Indiana
snap their long winning streak again, beating the Pacers 107-92 for
their 14th straight win.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, whose 16-game winning streak was ended in Indiana in
January, jumped out to a 30-16 advantage at the end of the first
quarter, and the Pacers got no closer than nine the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   When Indiana threatened, moving within 82-73 early in the fourth
period, O'Neal took charge, scoring Los Angeles' first nine points
of the quarter to help them pull away again.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant added 22 points and had seven assists for Los
Angeles, and reserve Robert Horry added 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller didn't get his first basket until 3:05 before
halftime, but finished with 22 points for the Pacers. Austin
Croshere added 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won the matchup of the team with the best record in
the Western Conference against the team with the top mark in the
East. Los Angeles improved to 21-2 against Eastern teams.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which has been a power at home this season but a
pushover on the road, has the Eastern Conference's best record,
39-19. Los Angeles is a league-best 48-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers draw another visitor from the other coast on Sunday,
when they try to extend their streak to 15 straight in a matchup
against Miami, which has the second-best record in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana was coming off its worst defeat in nearly two years, a
118-87 drubbing Thursday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers halted the Lakers' 16-game run, the league's longest
so far this season, with a 111-102 victory at Indianapolis on Jan.
14.
</P>
<P>
   After leading taking a 14-point lead into the second quarter,
the Lakers extended it to 21 on Horry's jumper that made it 50-29
with 3:21 before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 16 points and 10 rebounds by halftime, when Los
Angeles led 56-39.
</P>
<P>
   He powered the Lakers to their early lead, scoring seven points
during a 12-2 run over 2:22 span late in the opening period, as the
Lakers opened a 28-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Bryant outscored the entire Indiana team in the
opening quarter, with O'Neal getting 11 and Bryant 8 and the Pacers
scoring only 16.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Pacers fell to 13-17 on the road. They're a drastically
different team at home, where they are 26-2. The Lakers have been
far more consistent, going 21-7 on the road, 27-4 at home. ... The
Lakers began their losing streak after their worst loss of the
season, 105-81 at San Antonio. Los Angeles came back the next game
to beat Utah 113-67, the fewest points ever scored by a Lakers'
opponent and Los Angeles' most lopsided win since a 47-point romp
over Miami in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
