<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gen. Pinochet Arrives in Chile  </HEADLINE>
By BILL CORMIER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Former dictator Augusto Pinochet returned
home to sleep in his own bed for the first time in 503 days,
cheered by thousands of supporters after narrowly avoiding
prosecution abroad for alleged human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But his homecoming from Britain stirred new calls by Pinochet's
opponents for him to be put on trial at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Justice! Justice!'' about 200 opponents of his 1973-90 rule
chanted during a Friday night vigil outside the government palace.
</P>
<P>
   Many held up photographs of loved ones who were among more than
3,000 people who died or disappeared at hands of Pinochet's secret
police after he toppled elected Marxist President Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, arriving Friday morning after a 24-hour trip from
London aboard a Chilean air force plane, was lowered to the tarmac
in a wheelchair on an improvised elevator.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled to family and friends, appearing to make scant use of
a metal cane held in one hand. Hours after he checked into a
military hospital for medical tests, he was whisked by armored car
to his Santiago home, heavily guarded by rifle-toting troops in
camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's return also brings home to Chile the question of
whether to put him on trial. For 16 months Britain detained him
while it considered a request to extradite him to Spain to face
charges, but then set him free, saying he was too ill for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile, where the population is sharply divided over his
17-year-rule, supporters gave him a welcome that clearly
demonstrated the backing he enjoys from the armed forces,
right-wing politicians and prominent businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Augusto Pinochet rescued our country!'' exclaimed Ana Maria
Aguirre, 51, waving a large poster of Pinochet as he left the
military hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She said Chile had been slipping into chaos under Allende before
Pinochet and his fellow officers stepped in with their bloody coup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pinochet! Pinochet! Gracias!'' many in the crowd shouted, as
they were held back by police around the gates of the hospital.
Many wore headbands inscribed with Pinochet's name, or waved red,
white and blue Chilean flags.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Figueroa, a 22-year-old student, said he was overjoyed.
''I am just so happy, I can't believe we have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Pinochet appeared more robust than expected
because he was back at last on Chilean soil. ''He is hardy, he is a
soldier and he found strength upon returning home,'' Figueroa said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet left the hospital about nine hours later amid extremely
tight security. Troops swiftly shut the doors of his white-walled
compound behind his car when he reached home.
</P>
<P>
   Across the city, dozens of human rights activists and relatives
of dissidents who disappeared during Pinochet's regime held a vigil
in front of the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrator, Javier Aguilo, called Pinochet's return ''a
shame for our country.'' Other groups protested the government's
role in gaining Pinochet's release.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in London on Oct. 16, 1998, on a warrant
issued by a Spanish judge.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Home Secretary Jack Straw ordered Pinochet released
Thursday, saying an independent medical examination had found the
former dictator physically and mentally unfit for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights groups maintained that he looks healthy and
called his illness a ruse to avoid being extradited.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pinochet is not as sick as they say. And it has been proved
today with the kind of reception they organized for him,'' said
Viviana Diaz, head of an organization of relatives of people who
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Straw's final report on Pinochet said doctors found it unlikely
the general could fake mental incapacitation, and Chile's interior
minister dismissed claims of fakery.
</P>
<P>
   Now opponents are focusing on a trial in Chile, something that
many say is no longer the impossibility it once was considered.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's opponents have moved to have him stripped of the
immunity he enjoys as a senator for life. Judge Juan Guzman, who is
investigating about 60 cases against Pinochet, has forwarded the
petition to an appeals court for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist groups, chanting ''Pinochet, assassin,'' marched to the
Court of Appeals to express support for Guzman, who has ordered new
medical tests for Pinochet to help determine whether he can be
tried in Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
