<DOCNO> APW20000304.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old South, Civil Rights Cross Paths  </HEADLINE>
By JAY REEVES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- The Civil War collides with the civil
rights movement in Alabama this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A group that wants the South to once again split from the United
States will hold a rally today at the Capitol amid waving
Confederate flags, a day before President Clinton visits Selma to
commemorate a landmark civil rights event.
</P>
<P>
   As much as ever, the regionalism and rebellion symbolized by the
Confederate battle flag will be juxtaposed against the dogged
determination expressed in the old civil rights song ''We Shall
Overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the two sides may feed off each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''Extremists on one end of the political spectrum sort of need
extremists on the other end,'' said Jess Brown, a historian at
Athens State University.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP and other black groups contend the flag is a racist
symbol of oppression and slavery. Supporters say it honors their
Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   For today's rally at the Statehouse, bagpipers will join Civil
War re-enactors dressed in woolly gray uniforms to parade up
historic Dexter Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was organized by the Tuscaloosa-based League of the
South. The group, which claims as many as 10,000 members, will
issue a ''Declaration of Southern Cultural Independence'' as part
of its call for the South to become a separate nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're doing here is stating that we don't like the modern
culture that is being forced upon us. We are declaring war on
that,'' said John Cripps, a rally organizer and League chairman in
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say at least 20 of the League's 27 state chapters
will be represented to the Alabama Capitol, where Jefferson Davis
took the oath as president of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's important that we get out the truth about what
the war for Southern independence was about,'' said Mac Watters of
Panama City, Fla. ''The war was about states' rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on Sunday, Clinton will lead marchers across Selma's
Edmund Pettus Bridge to mark the 35th anniversary of ''Bloody
Sunday,'' when state troopers and sheriff's officers used clubs and
tear gas to turn back voting rights demonstrators trying to march
to Montgomery, 54 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, under the protection of a federal court, the
Rev. Martin Luther King led hundreds of people on the long walk to
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the ugly violence of Bloody Sunday and the eventual
Selma-to-Montgomery march aroused the nation and helped spur
passage of the Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Showing how much things have changed in 35 years, longtime Selma
Mayor Joe Smitherman -- a former segregationist -- is distancing
himself from the Confederates and embracing Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman has never participated in a ''Bloody Sunday''
commemorative walk across the bridge, but said he wouldn't mind
joining the president during the crossing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever they want me to do I'll participate in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first president to come to Selma for the
commemoration, organized in part by the National Voting Rights
Museum, which he will tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is important enough for the most powerful person in the
world to come,'' said Democratic state Sen. Hank Sanders, of Selma.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Lewis, a Georgia Democrat who suffered a
fractured skull during the Bloody Sunday fracas on March 7, 1965,
will lead a delegation of at least 16 members of Congress attending
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' group, including clergy and other civil rights figures,
planned tours of civil rights sites in Montgomery and Birmingham
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The League of the South, meanwhile, encouraged members and
supporters to attend the Capitol rally in opposition to the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights group and other activists have organized a
tourism boycott against South Carolina until the state removes the
flag from atop the Statehouse dome. South Carolina is the only
state that still flies the flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0118 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
