<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign 2000 Notes and Quotes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- If John Rocker can get a
vice
presidential pardon after atoning for bigoted remarks, why not
George W. Bush for his visit to Bob Jones University?
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reporter for Atlanta's WSB-TV put the question to Al Gore, who
has spoken forgivingly of Rocker, the Atlanta Braves relief
pitcher, for seeking counseling and atonement after he was
suspended for making bigoted comments. Gore has condemned his
Republican rival, Bush, for launching his Southern campaign at the
racially segregated Bob Jones University, a center of anti-Catholic
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bill! Bill! How long did you work on that question?'' Gore
said to the reporter, who was conducting the interview via
satellite as Gore campaigned in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a distinction between ''a young person who made a
mistake'' (Rocker is 25; Bush, 54) and ''somebody in Gov. Bush's
position,'' Gore said both can learn from their errors and overcome
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think that someone aspiring to national leadership has
to meet a somewhat higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
   22,712 -- Number of precincts in California's March 7 primary, as
of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   255 -- Number of precincts in Rhode Island's March 7 primary, as
of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER'S VOICE
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm actually a Republican. I came out for the hot dogs and the
excitement. Being from New Jersey, I do like Bill Bradley ... He's
such a more dynamic figure than Al Gore is. I don't know -- maybe
that doesn't translate to the Midwest as well as it does here in
the Northeast.'' -- Luke Littleton, of Franklin, N.J. who nabbed a
free hot dog from Bill Bradley during a campaign appearance
Thursday at Gray's Papaya hot dog stand in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander emerged from an Atlanta church service saying he
was pressing on with his campaign for the GOP nomination, despite
House Speaker Newt Gingrich's suggestion that he should consider
bowing out. ''This is just the first inning in the campaign. I'll
swing a little harder and have a better second inning.'' He quit
the race three days later.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S ROUNDUP:
</P>
<P>
   John McCain charged that Bush supporters were waging a shadowy
effort to ''hijack'' the race by spending $2 million on a TV ad
criticizing his environmental record. McCain also criticized as
misleading a Bush ad that suggests McCain opposes federal funding
for breast cancer research. Bush headed to a breast cancer research
center in New York to emphasize his criticism of McCain for listing
some breast cancer projects as pork-barrel spending. The ad
features a breast cancer survivor saying America deserves ''a
candidate with a record on women's issues we can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Gore ripped Bush for saying during a debate he had
''no problem with trigger locks being sold.'' ''Is that what passes
for courage on the Republican side of this contest?'' asked Gore,
who, like Bradley, wants to make child-safety locks mandatory on
all handguns. Bradley, in Maine, called the race ''a choice between
the politics of division, of exaggerated and unfulfilled promises,
and a politics based upon belief, conviction and straight talk.''
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND'S TRAIL:
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigns in New York today before flying to Austin for the
night. On Sunday he will appear on a morning talk show before
flying to California. McCain campaigns in New England and New York
as well, and flies to California on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigns in New York and Missouri today, and flies east
to campaign in Maryland Sunday. Gore campaigns today in Boston and
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
