<DOCNO> APW20000304.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker: Census Critic Deceptive  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fund-raising letter from a critic of the
Census Bureau looks so much like an official agency document that
the public could mistake it for a real census form now being sent
to households, says a lawmaker who wants the group to put its
mailing on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., ranking member of the House
Government Reform Committee census panel, asked the Postal Service
to look into the mailing from the Southeastern Legal Foundation,
claiming it violated federal postal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The words ''IMPORTANT 2000 CENSUS MATERIALS ENCLOSED'' and ''BUY
U.S. SAVINGS BONDS'' appear in bold letters above the address label
on the group's mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Atlanta-based nonprofit foundation asks recipients
to sign a petition requesting the Census Bureau not to use a
statistical method known as sampling when compiling data from the
upcoming count. It also asks for a donation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This kind of behavior crosses the line. When people see that
this solicitation is a shameless fake, I know that they will throw
it out,'' said Maloney, who supports sampling. ''But I am afraid
that when the real mailing comes they might throw it out as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The mailings have been sent to 250,000 households since January.
The foundation's executive director said they don't resemble Census
Bureau forms.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't conceive of why it's considered deceptive,'' said
Matthew Glavin. ''There is no similarity at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Census questionnaires come in envelopes that have the bureau's
''Census 2000'' logo and a Department of Commerce return address.
Delivery to rural homes began Friday, and by the end of the month
most of the country's 115 million households should have one.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. postal inspector Daniel Mihalko said he had yet to see the
foundation's mailing, and that the Postal Service had not received
any consumer complaints about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Census Bureau has had experience over the last several
decades with mailings that are official-looking, and our priority
is to make sure that the American public is educated about what
actual census forms envelopes look like,'' Census Bureau spokesman
Steve Jost said.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Legal Foundation was a plaintiff in a case last
year in which the Supreme Court ruled that the federal government
must use non-sampled, or raw, Census 2000 data to reapportion
Congressional seats. States must decide which data set to use for
redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   Glavin suggested Maloney's attack might be revenge for his
refusal to co-sign a letter with her urging Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, a Republican, to reveal whether he would allow the Census
Bureau to release sampled numbers should Bush become president.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials estimate they undercounted the population by
about 4 million in 1990, mostly minorities and inner-city residents
who tend to vote Democrat, and that sampling improves accuracy. The
GOP fears sampled data could redraw political lines to their
disadvantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
