<HEADLINE> Amtrak Settles Discrimination Suit  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in nine months, Amtrak has
settled a racial discrimination suit, the latest alleging the
national railway condoned hostile work conditions for blacks that
created a ''segregated work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak did not admit any wrongdoing in the settlement announced
on Friday, but the railway agreed to change company policies. And
the settlement, which must be approved by a federal judge, sets up
a $16 million fund to provide economic relief to 800 to 1,000 black
employees who suffered discrimination since 1995 and as many as
4,000 black job applicants Amtrak turned away.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by 13 black members of the Brotherhood of
Maintenance of Way Employees who build and maintain railroad tracks
for Amtrak's engineering department in the Northeast corridor
between Washington and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a clear situation where a rising tide will float all
boats,'' Jed Dodd, an official with the union, said in praising the
agreement. ''All working whites and blacks are going to benefit
from the injunctive provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak President George Warrington said settling out-of-court
was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''Amtrak is committed to a cultural change at the company that
will not only make Amtrak a better place in which to work, but also
will enable us to be more responsive to the diverse marketplace we
serve,'' he said. ''We have already taken a number of important
steps in transforming the company's culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak has agreed to change policies affecting hiring,
certification, discipline, training and advancement and computerize
personnel files and applications, said Maia Caplan, a Washington
attorney for employees who filed the federal class action suit in
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot that Amtrak has agreed to here that would not
have happened if this had gone into litigation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleged that white managers separated employees into
white and black work crews, and then gave white workers better
assignments and kept them from being bumped by black employees with
more seniority. They claimed white work crews were told in advance
about drug tests and that white employees suspected of possibly
failing the tests were encouraged to take the day off.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said white supervisors called black employees
''boys'' and made comments like ''you people like watermelon'' and
''all you people lie.'' When a black employee's beeper sounded
during a meeting, one white manager remarked that ''someone's drug
deal is going down,'' the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs also complained in the suit that management did
not promptly remove a racial epithet scrawled on company property
and that a white manager once told a black worker that white
members of a track-laying crew were in the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The result has been a substantially segregated work force,''
the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement settles the first of three discrimination suits
filed against Amtrak in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Amtrak settled a suit filed by black managers and
employees seeking management positions. The railway agreed to
change company policies and set up an $8 million fund to compensate
those who sued. The remaining suit, which has not been resolved,
was filed in November 1999 by 24 current and former workers who
allege that Amtrak's Intercity Strategic Business Unit, which
operates in 29 states, discriminates against black workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0135 </TRAILER>
