<HEADLINE> PM-NY--NY Senate-Clinton, Bjt,580  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is inching forward in her
comments about the Amadou Diallo killing, saying she supports a
federal investigation into the unarmed immigrant's death at the
hands of police but cannot comment on whether a civil rights
prosecution is merited.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Justice Department should look into it and should make a
decision as to whether or not it will proceed,'' she told reporters
Friday. ''And that's up to the Justice Department to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had previously declined to say whether she thought
federal investigators should look into the Diallo case. The four
officers who shot at Diallo 41 times were acquitted by an Albany
jury last week, angering many New Yorkers and prompting calls for a
federal civil rights prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke cautiously Friday, and did not say whether
she thought the officers should be prosecuted again.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a decision that is going to be made by the people who
should be making it,'' she said, explaining that Justice Department
lawyers would look carefully at the facts of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder met in Washington, D.C.,
Thursday with Diallo's parents and other supporters, who pressed
the Justice Department to take on the case. Holder made no
guarantee that charges would be sought and said in a statement that
''the standard to proceed in federal court is high.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke after meeting in midtown Manhattan with
leaders of the gun control group PAX, founded by Daniel Gross,
whose brother Matthew was badly injured in a 1997 shooting atop the
Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's focus on guns came in the wake of a 6-year-old
Michigan girl's death Tuesday at the hands of a 6-year-old
classmate. The tragedy has brought new attention to the gun control
debate, and President Clinton sought to rally support this week for
legislation requiring gun safety locks and gun show background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton said she plans to participate in a Million Mom
March planned for Washington, D.C., on Mother's Day to urge tougher
gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would invite thousands and thousands of New Yorkers to join
this march calling on Congress to make the tough decisions to
protect our children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether New York has a problem with police brutality -- a
heated issue in recent days -- she replied, ''New York City
obviously has a problem when an innocent unarmed man is gunned
down. ... We need to take steps to make sure that never happens
again.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not specify what should be done, but called for greater
understanding between residents and police and indicated she would
talk more about the issue in a speech at Riverside Church on
Sunday. Many black and Hispanic New Yorkers have accused the police
of racial profiling and said officers are too ready to use violence
against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very convinced that we can continue to decrease the crime
rate and increase the trust rate in New York,'' she said. ''There
is a lot that we could do with the right kind of leadership, that
brings people together and reaches out to try to understand what
it's like to be on the other side. ... I hope that our efforts can
help to ... bring those who are committed to protecting us together
with people who need protection and also deserve respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
