<HEADLINE> NATO Peacekeepers Push Ahead  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO-led peacekeepers have
pledged to push ahead with resettling ethnic Albanians on the north
side of this divided town, despite violent protests by Serbs and
concern from human rights workers.
</P>
<P>
   French troops fired tear gas and stun grenades Friday to break
through a crowd of angry Serbs blocking an apartment complex.
Ethnic Albanians were trying to return to the apartments after
being forced out in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a second attempt, Danish armored personnel carriers carrying
41 ethnic Albanians lumbered across the Ibar River, which divides
the two communities, pushing through the crowd to reach the
buildings. The Serbs rushed at French troops, who fired more tear
gas and stun grenades to break a path.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, criticized the latest
attempt at repatriation and said the situation was too tense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The events of today -- the fact that they had to be moved with
armored personnel carriers -- that there was barbed wire and tear
gas -- does not indicate the conditions for safe return,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest effort to send home dozens of ethnic Albanian
families came after stone-throwing Serbs forced officials to abort
an earlier attempt to move the ethnic Albanians across a footbridge
linking the north and south banks of the river. Troops disassembled
the bridge earlier because of high water.
</P>
<P>
   Five French peacekeepers were injured in Friday's standoff,
according to French Gen. Pierre de Saqui de Sannes, the NATO
commander in charge of northern Kosovo. Nine Serbs were treated for
injuries, authorities at the local hospital said.
</P>
<P>
   De Saqui de Sannes defended the action as necessary to move the
peace effort forward.
</P>
<P>
   ''All initiatives create tension, but inaction would be worse,''
he said. ''Time is playing against peace here, if we do nothing, we
will head towards catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that peacekeepers would provide around-the-clock
security inside and outside the apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovska Mitrovica, 20 miles northwest of Pristina, has been the
scene of repeated ethnic unrest in recent weeks, resulting in
several deaths and dozens of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed violence has thwarted efforts by NATO and Kosovo's
U.N. administration to establish normality in the Serbian province,
eight months after NATO's 78-day bombing campaign forced an end to
the Serb crackdown in Kosovo and the pullout of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of Serb frustrations in Kosovo, about 1,000 people
gathered in front of a Serbian Orthodox church in southeastern
Kosovo to protest the recent killing of a prominent Serb doctor
there, the state-run Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned Friday that the recent
violence in Kosovska Mitrovica could spread within Kosovo and spill
over into southern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic unrest indicates that progress made since NATO forces
moved into Kosovo in June ''is not yet irreversible,'' Annan said
in a 46-page report to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops and Kosovo's U.N. administration consider the area
east of Kosovo's boundary with Serbia ''to be extremely volatile at
present,'' he said, adding that ''the situation there causes great
concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0151 </TRAILER>
