<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $40B Aviation Spending Bill Close  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers will try again next week to find
common ground on a major aviation spending bill after at least one
key senator objected to a compromise that has been months in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would authorize $40 billion over three years for
safety, construction and operating programs of the Federal Aviation
Administration, and includes a raise in passenger taxes, more money
for small airports and more flights from several of the nation's
busiest airports.
</P>
<P>
   Federal funding for new airport projects has been held up by
Congress' failure to pass a bill by the beginning of the fiscal
year last Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The safety and modernization goals of the bill have wide
bipartisan support, but it has languished mainly because of a
dispute between House Transportation Committee Chairman Bud
Shuster, R-Pa., and some senators over the Aviation Trust Fund,
which collects some $10 billion a year in user fees.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster wanted to separate that fund from the general budget so
that its revenues could go only to aviation improvement. But
senators said that would undercut the authority of the budget and
appropriations committees that determine spending levels every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., helped craft a
compromise under which the trust fund would stay in the general
budget but spending for aviation projects would at least equal the
revenues and interest from the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, said the House, without consulting him,
added language that erected a new parliamentary hurdle to waiving
the trust fund provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he was ''really pained'' and that eight or nine
senators would join him in opposing the compromise. ''It's
untenable for many of us that it was rewritten after an agreement
had been reached,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he had planned to bring the compromise to the Senate
floor Tuesday or Wednesday, but with Stevens' objections the bill
''could be in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also allows airports to increase their passenger taxes,
called Passenger Facility Charges, from the current ceiling of $3
per person to $4.50. If all airports imposed the increase, it could
bring in up to $700 million more a year for local construction and
modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster had sought to double the cap to $6, but Senate
negotiators, led by Commerce Committee Chairman John McCain,
R-Ariz., were against any increase. McCain, a GOP presidential
contender, is against any tax increases, spokeswoman Pia Pialorsi
said.
</P>
<P>
   House officials said airports seeking to raise their passenger
fees must show that the increase would significantly help safety,
capacity, noise abatement or security and that they needed funding
above what they receive under the Airport Improvement Program.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would nearly double grants for airport modernization,
with the minimum entitlement for smaller airports going from
$500,000 to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also would eliminate the ''high density rule''
established in 1969 to limit flights from New York's Kennedy and La
Guardia airports and Chicago's O'Hare, taking effect in 2007 in New
York and 2002 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Slots -- one slot is a landing or takeoff -- at Washington's
Reagan National Airport would be increased by 24, with 12 of those
reserved for flights beyond the 1,250-mile ''perimeter rule'' in
place since 1986. McCain had pushed hard for this as part of an
effort to increase flights to smaller, less-competitive airports.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation amends the 1920 Death on the High Seas Act,
which bars families of those lost in air disasters -- such as the
1996 TWA 800 crash that killed 230 people just off Long Island,
N.Y. -- from collecting non-economic damages.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, the 1920 law would not apply to air crashes
within 12 nautical miles of the U.S. shoreline. It would be
retroactive to the day before the TWA crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Doesn't Rule Out US Troops  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- American troops could be sent to Europe
to quell conflicts even after the creation of a new European
security force, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright says after
high-level meetings here.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision will be based on U.S. national interest, Albright
said Friday while welcoming plans to establish a rapid reaction
force of 50,000 to 60,000 European troops by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to reduce Europe's reliance on American diplomacy
and firepower to quell European conflicts. Albright was briefed at
a meeting with European Union officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we will always judge what is in our national interest
as to when we are part of a military action,'' Albright said at a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a speech aboard the USS Wasp, a helicopter carrier
making a stop here on its way to the Mediterranean for exercises,
Albright said ''we must create both a more capable Europe and a
stronger alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to say whether the European force, had it been in
existence, could have put down the ethnic violence in the Balkans
that led to a NATO attack with U.S. troops now serving as
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must never let the bonds between Europe and the America
erode,'' Albright said. ''These are the bonds that defeated Hitler
and defended freedom through decades of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Russia yielded to demands that it permit European human
rights experts into Chechnya to look for evidence that civilians
were mistreated as the Russian army crushed Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has jockeyed with the United States and its European
allies for months, and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov's offer was
received with considerable skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   But Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, who holds the
rotating presidency of the European Union, welcomed the Russian
response. ''The facts point to change in the situation,'' Gama
said. ''A definitive solution has not been found, but things are
beginning to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   Denying all the while that the bloodied area was sealed off from
outside observers and the media as Russian troops hammered Grozny,
the capital, into submission, Ivanov said his government was taking
''significant steps'' to allay Western misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Western reporters who got into Chechnya of
disseminating ''false and twisted information'' and lectured a
French journalist that her newspaper printed unbalanced accounts of
the Russian offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Russia based its assault in the Caucasus on the twofold argument
that it had a right to stop Chechnya from seceding from Russia, and
the rebellion was fomented by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov held to this argument Friday. He said the fight against
separatism, extremism and nationalism ''in all forms is our common
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to the onsite surveys by experts including the Red
Cross' president at a joint session with senior American and
European officials. The meeting marked another step in coordinating
policy with Russia on such diverse topics as peacekeeping in the
Balkans and nuclear safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0153 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Van Crash Kills Seven  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) -- A speeding van crashed and burst into
flames Friday killing a woman and six children, believed to be
hers, the California Highway Patrol said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said firefighters arriving on the scene found a man
at the side of the road sobbing, ''I've lost my family.'' The man,
believed to be the children's father, suffered only a broken thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that they blew a tire crossed the double yellow
lines, hit a tree, crossed back over, possibly flipped over and
became fully engulfed in flames,'' said Sgt. Rich Luciano.
</P>
<P>
   The van apparently was speeding, but police do not know who was
driving, Luciano said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened about 7:30 p.m. just north of Interstate
580 in Livermore, about 45 miles east of San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0156 </TRAILER>
