<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Rain Looms in Mozambique
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- Just as floodwaters began to recede and more
rescue boats arrived in battered and flood-swollen Mozambique, a new threat
loomed: more rain. A storm hovering over the Indian Ocean threatened to hit this
impoverished southeastern African country Saturday as thousands of people who
had been stranded in treetops for a week finally made their way to dry ground.
But despite the dramatic drop in flood levels in at least one area, which came
unexpectedly Friday, rescue workers estimated up to 15,000 people remained
trapped in the central Save River valley. They also warned of the possibility of
outbreaks of disease.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gen. Pinochet Arrives in Chile
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Former dictator Augusto Pinochet returned home to
sleep in his own bed for the first time in 503 days, cheered by thousands of
supporters after narrowly avoiding prosecution abroad for alleged human rights
abuses. But his homecoming from Britain stirred new calls by Pinochet's
opponents for him to be put on trial at home. ''Justice! Justice!'' about 200
opponents of his 1973-90 rule chanted during a Friday night vigil outside the
government palace. Many held up photographs of loved ones who were among more
than 3,000 people who died or disappeared at hands of Pinochet's secret police
after he toppled elected Marxist President Salvador Allende.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bob Jones Univ. Drops Race Date Ban
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Bob Jones University will drop its ban on interracial
dating, Bob Jones III said on CNN's ''Larry King Live'' Friday night. ''As of
today, right now, we're dropping it,'' Jones III said. Criticism followed after
Republican Presidential Candidate George W. Bush visited the school last month.
The ban on interracial dating was just one criticism Bush faced after his visit
to the Greenville school. Bush apologized earlier this week for failing to
criticize the anti-Catholic views of the university when he visited last month.
During his appearance there, the Texas governor told his audience that he shared
their values.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haiti Postpones Elections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Dogged by organizational problems that left
more than 1 million voters unregistered, Haiti on Friday postponed March 19
elections, without specifying a new date. The announcement came only hours after
the U.N. Security Council urged Haiti to stick ''as closely as possible'' to its
schedule for elections, which it said were crucial to the Caribbean nation's
fledgling democracy. ''A new electoral timetable for the balloting will be
published as soon as possible,'' said electoral council spokesman Roland
Sainristil. He cited ''innumerable difficulties surrounding voter
registration.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Slain Michigan Girl Mourned
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- At a memorial service Friday night, some 1,000 mourners
grieved for Kayla Rolland, the 6-year-old girl who was shot to death in her
elementary school, allegedly by a 6-year-old classmate. Kayla, in a red dress,
lay in an open casket, a small doll of the TV character Barney beneath it. In
her hands was a small card with a poem titled ''I'm free.'' The boy who shot
Kayla has told police that it was an accident and that he meant only to scare
her. The two are believed to have scuffled on the playground the day before. No
charges are expected against the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 202.28; Nasdaq Up 160.28
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks climbed higher Friday after government data showed
some easing of the tight labor market. The Dow Jones industrial average rose
202.28 points to close at 10,367.20. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,715-1,271. For the week, the blue-chip index rose 505.08 points, its best
performance since July. The Nasdaq composite index rose 160.28 to 4,914.79,
another record high.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trinidad Wins WBA Title
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Felix Trinidad Jr. got hot in the second half of the fight
on a cool desert night and won the WBA super welterweight championship on a
one-sided decision over David Reid. The IBF-WBC welterweight champion from
Puerto Rico was knocked down in the third round Friday night outdoors at Caesars
Palace and had trouble getting though Reid's defense. Trinidad took control of
the fight, knocking down Reid in the seventh round, ripping a cut over his right
eye in the eighth and knocking him down three times in the 11th.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
