<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High school student rally against police tactics  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Three hundred high school students
skipped
classes Friday and marched over the Brooklyn Bridge to protest
police tactics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''I've been at high school over three years and this is the
first time I've had pride in my high school,'' said Raime
Masket-Roth, a 17-year-old Stuyvesant High School senior.
</P>
<P>
   He said the protesters, who held rallies in Brooklyn and in City
Hall Park, wanted to deliver a message to the city and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani that the police department must change.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was not in City Hall at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Friday, a jury in Albany found officers Kenneth Boss,
Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy innocent of murder
in the Feb. 4, 1999, shooting of Diallo. The unarmed immigrant from
Guinea died in a 41-bullet barrage in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, a plainclothes officer shot and killed
Malcolm Ferguson, an unarmed, paroled drug dealer, just three
blocks from Diallo's home. Ferguson had participated in a protest
of the Diallo verdict last week and was detained for resisting
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters who crossed the bridge from Manhattan on Friday
joined more than 100 other high school students waiting behind
police barricades in the street across from the state court
building in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was held near the federal courthouse, where a jury was
deliberating the fate of three officers accused of a cover-up in
the August 1997 police-station torture of Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The students, many of them wearing backpacks full of books,
chanted ''No Justice, No Peace,'' as several dozen relaxed police
officers stood on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a wallet, not a gun,'' read one sign, which referred to
the claim by police that Diallo had pulled a wallet out of his
pocket which the officers thought was a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''America's future won't stand for this,'' read another sign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not every cop is a bad cop but police brutality has got to
stop,'' read still another, attracting the attention of Norman
Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ''That sign was very balanced and I personally went over and
commended the young woman who made it,'' said Siegel, who crossed
the bridge with the students after they asked him to ensure the
protest was conducted legally. ''Young people show models of
leadership that we can follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Laila Roman, 17, a Beacon High School student, said police
brutality was on the minds of many young people. ''It's hard that
we have to fear the people that are out there to protect us,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another protester, Monica Rose, said it would be hard to change
the police department until officers are better paid and better
educated.
</P>
<P>
   As the rally continued for an hour with students reading poetry,
delivering brief speeches and singing, ''We Shall Overcome,'' three
girls made an early exit, sneaking away under a blue barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why I wasted my time coming down here,'' one of
them said loud enough for her friends and anyone else nearby to
hear. ''I gotta get my hair done.''
</P>
<P>
   As about 300 of her fellow students marched back across the
bridge to City Hall, they chanted ''41'' -- the number of shots
fired at Diallo -- before holding a ''teach-in'' at City Hall Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
