<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Visit Philippines Volcano  </HEADLINE>
By OLIVER TEVES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEGAZPI, Philippines (AP) -- While tens of thousands of Filipinos
displaced by eruptions of the Mayon volcano cope with life in
crammed evacuation centers, tourists are flocking here to watch it,
tourism officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Since the volcano began erupting Feb. 24, foreign tourists have
become a frequent sight in the city square and at the ruins of the
Cagsawa church, which was destroyed by an eruption in 1814.
</P>
<P>
   The 18 hotels and lodging houses in Legazpi, the nearest city,
are reporting a 55 percent occupancy rate, up from only 5 percent
before the eruptions, the regional Department of Tourism office
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, more than 66,000 villagers have been forced
from their homes by the eruptions, which have already destroyed
more than 16,000 acres of crops valued at about $4.1 million,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Ligao, the heavy ash fall killed fish in more than 250
acres of fish ponds by clogging their gills.
</P>
<P>
   Mayon remained relatively quiet for a third day Friday, but
scientists said seismographs showed magma is still rising in the
mountain, indicating a likelihood of future eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The volcano, famous for its near-perfect conical shape, has
always been a modest tourist attraction. But arrivals have risen
sharply since it began erupting.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists have come to Albay province, about 215 miles southeast
of Manila, to watch in awe as Mayon spewed fountains of lava that
formed a flaming red and orange river down its slopes.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists are prohibited from climbing the 8,118-foot volcano
because of safety concerns, said Diosdado Raneses of the city's
tourism office.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city is not actively campaigning for tourists to
visit Mayon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can really feel the suffering of our people,'' he said. ''No
one is trying to ride on this. The priority is still the
evacuees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice farmers had been almost ready to harvest their crops when
the eruptions came.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would have harvested in three weeks, but the ash now has
stunted the rice's growth,'' said Teodorico Residilla, a town
council member.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers were cutting their rice early and feeding it to
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The volcanology institute warned that rains may trigger
avalanches of volcanic mud and debris left on Mayon's slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Daep, head of the provincial disaster management office,
said the number of evacuees could rise to 80,000 if avalanches
occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
