<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NC Trooper Claims Racial Profiling  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT MOONEYHAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- A black North Carolina state trooper who
says he was stopped randomly while off-duty and ordered out of his
car at gunpoint is suing two police officers and the city of
Jacksonville for alleged racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, nine-year patrol veteran Todd Williams says he
was stopped for ''fitting a racial profile, to wit: 'a black person
driving a luxury vehicle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 30, said Friday that in June two white officers
ordered him out of his Lexus at gunpoint although he had promptly
obeyed an officer's request to pull over.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told the officers he was a state trooper and demanded
to know why he was stopped. The officers told him he was driving 65
mph in a 55 mph zone, he said. Williams denies he was speeding.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville Police Chief Ken Bumgarner said agents from the
State Bureau of Investigation viewed a video of the traffic stop
recorded from a camera in the accused officers' vehicle and found
no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the lawsuit seeks damages exceeding $10,000 for
humiliation, emotional distress and loss of liberty, Williams said
he doesn't want money. Instead, he said he hopes his lawsuit makes
police in Jacksonville, 100 miles southeast of Raleigh, rethink how
they conduct traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   He said he filed the lawsuit only after city officials refused
to do anything about his complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, North Carolina began requiring Williams and
other state law enforcement officers to record the race of every
motorist they stop. Connecticut also has the same requirement, and
at least 18 other states are considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Figures released this week by the North Carolina Highway Patrol
show that in the first month traffic stops were monitored, black
motorists were pulled over in numbers proportional to their
population. However, black and Hispanic motorists and passengers
were searched in disproportionate numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
