<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds EPA Pollution Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency is moving
ahead on a regulation requiring 19 states to take steps to reduce
the interstate drifting of pollution, especially from coal-burning
power plants.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the U. S. Court of Appeals gave the go-ahead for the
new rule Friday, upholding a 1998 EPA regulation aimed at plants in
the Ohio Valley that the agency says send smog-causing chemicals
into the Northeast, aggravating air quality problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-1 decision was a major victory for the EPA and
air-pollution control officials in the Northeast, but a setback for
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   While upholding the EPA's smog directive in general, the court
said in the case of three additional states -- Missouri, Wisconsin
and Georgia -- the rule should be further reviewed by the courts.
EPA officials said that will not inhibit the agency action against
the 19 states, from Massachusetts to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA issued the regulation in October 1998 in an attempt to
reduce the long-distance travel of smog-causing nitrogen oxide that
spews out of tall utility smokestacks that dot the Ohio Valley,
Midwest and parts of the South. But the rules were locked in limbo
last May because of a lawsuit and a temporary blocking order by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   All 22 states were to have submitted plans for the pollution
reductions by last September, but those plans never materialized
because of the lawsuit. The new controls are to be required by 2003
for some plants and 2005 for others.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Missouri, Wisconsin and Georgia, the
appeals panel ruled that the EPA had acted properly. It said the
regulation ''reasonably establishes (pollution) reduction levels''
while leaving the question of how to accomplish those reductions to
the states.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision means that we again can move forward to bring
cleaner, healthier air to more than 138 million people living in
the eastern half of the United States,'' EPA Administrator Carol
Browner said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed by eight states that have the dirtiest
coal-burning plants, and operators of many of these plants in the
Ohio Valley and Midwest. It challenged the way the EPA determined
the source of the air pollution and how it considered the cost of
pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation targeted any state the EPA believed caused
pollution that drifted into another state, but the prime targets
were the Ohio Valley plants.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 states are Alabama, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois,
Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, North
Carolina, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island,
South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   While Wisconsin, Missouri and Georgia also were listed by the
EPA, the court said in the case of those states the agency would
have to make a better case. It was not clear Friday whether the
agency will pursue the matter with the three states.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Stephen Williams and Judith Rogers voted to uphold the
EPA regulation. Judge David Sentelle dissented, arguing that the
EPA ''has exceeded its statutory authority'' and should be reminded
''its mission is not (to be) a roving commission to achieve pure
air.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists applauded the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''This puts the agency on track to cut pollution from coal-fired
power plants in the eastern half of the United States by over a
million tons,'' said David Hawkins, an air quality specialist at
the Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Stanfield, of U.S.PIRG, another environmental group,
called it a ''huge victory for public health'' because the
coal-fired plants will be required to install additional pollution
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and politicians in the Northeast have argued
for years that those plants, which are allowed under federal law to
comply with less-stringent air pollution standards, spew out
hundreds of thousands of tons of smog-causing chemicals that drift
into the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grumet, executive director of the Northeast States for
Coordinated Air Use Management, said a study commission by his
group showed that 25 to 40 percent of the pollution from Ohio
Valley power plants drifts into the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities in the Ohio Valley and Midwest have argued that such
claims are exaggerated and that the Northeast's inability to meet
federal air quality standards stems from urban automobile traffic
and industrial pollution, not chemicals from power plants hundreds
of miles away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
