<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Find Racist Writings  </HEADLINE>
By TIM MOLLOY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKINSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Racist writings describing hatred toward
whites, Jews and Asians, were found in the apartment of a black man
accused in a shooting rampage that left three people dead in
suburban Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents released Friday said police found one paper
called ''The Satan List'' that contained the names of businesses
referred to as ''targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ronald Taylor, 39, was arraigned Friday on a third
count of criminal homicide after a third victim died.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Taylor -- who acknowledged to a judge that he has a
history of mental illness -- apparently became enraged over work
being done at his apartment and began screaming racial epithets at
repairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said he shot one of the men, killing him, set the
apartment on fire and walked to two fast-food restaurants, where he
shot four others.
</P>
<P>
   All five victims were white. That, and the writings, led police
to charge Taylor with ''ethnic intimidation'' -- a hate crime. The
FBI is also investigating for possible civil rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   James Ecker, Taylor's lawyer, declined comment Friday except to
say that his client feels bad about the victims. Taylor said
nothing at Friday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The night after the shootings, police and federal agents scoured
Taylor's fire-damaged apartment, finding several handwritten notes.
The actual writings were not released, but police described them in
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The writings called for ''Death to Jerusalem,'' referred to
''white trash,'' and listed ''various racist names and opinions''
about groups including whites, Jews, Asians, Italians, police, the
federal government and the news media, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be noted that in this case, all of those that were
shot or threatened by the suspect were white males,'' investigators
said. ''During the arson/shooting spree, the suspect came upon many
blacks, especially in the areas in and around the restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Fulton, assistant superintendent of Allegheny County
police, said the fast-food restaurants -- a McDonald's and a Burger
King -- were not on the ''Satan List'' of targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croat General Sentenced to 45 Years  </HEADLINE>
By SNJEZANA VUKIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- The 45-year prison sentence of a Bosnian
Croat general for atrocities committed by his soldiers could hamper
future cooperation between Croatia's new government and the U.N.
war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The court on Friday found Gen. Tihomir Blaskic guilty of
ordering an ''ethnic cleansing'' campaign against Muslim villages
in central Bosnia, which left hundreds dead and forced thousands
more to flee the area.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Croatia's newly elected, pro-Western government
criticized the verdict as too harsh because Blaskic -- who commanded
a Bosnian Croat militia during the 1992-95 war -- did not personally
take part in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is ''a really severe punishment which I believe will
have to be reviewed through the appeals procedure,'' said Premier
Ivica Racan.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling comes at a sensitive time in Croatia's cooperation
with the tribunal, based in The Hague, Netherlands. The new
government has promised to end years of stonewalling on extradition
requests and grant investigators access to alleged war crimes
sites.
</P>
<P>
   While Croatia's new leaders did not dismiss the ruling simply as
''anti-Croat,'' as was the habit of the former government of the
late President Franjo Tudjman, many see Blaskic as a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Blaskic, who surrendered to the tribunal voluntarily, ''ended up
as ... a pawn in the play where others pulled strings,'' said
Zlatko Kramaric, the leader of the Liberal Party, part of the new
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Racan insisted his Cabinet would live up to its promises of full
cooperation with the court. But Drazen Budisa, leader of the Social
Liberals -- Racan's partner in the ruling coalition -- said the
sentence will have ''an unfavorable effect'' on relations with the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Zdravko Tomac, deputy speaker of Parliament, went a step
further, saying the case represented ''a crisis situation'' for the
new government.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also could turn Croats against the tribunal, making
it harder for the government to get public support for its new
campaign of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Hague thought that with the new government in charge, we
wouldn't care for Bosnian Croats at all,'' said a 24-year-old
student, who only identified himself as Marin. ''Blaskic is a
different case.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling set an important precedent by characterizing the
Muslim-Croat fighting in Bosnia as an international conflict,
mirroring an earlier judgment that confirmed Yugoslavia's
involvement in the war on the side of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0236 </TRAILER>
