<HEADLINE> Anguilla Votes for New Government  </HEADLINE>
By WYCLIFFE RICHARDSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE VALLEY, Anguilla (AP) -- Voters on this Caribbean island have
handed a parliamentary majority to an alliance of opposition
parties, frustrating Chief Minister Hubert Hughes' efforts to keep
his post.
</P>
<P>
   The two-party coalition in this British territory -- led by
opposition leader Osbourne Fleming and Hughes' former finance
minister, Victor Banks -- denied Hughes' hoped-for majority by
capturing four of seven seats in Friday's vote for the House of
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   All seven incumbents were re-elected, but because of a political
realignment, Hughes was expected to lose his post to Fleming, who
had been tapped to become chief minister if the opposition won.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the election were to be presented later today to the
island's British governor, Peter Johnston, who was then to ask
Fleming's coalition to form a new government. The new chief
minister could be sworn in by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes held onto his district, while Banks -- tapped for finance
minister in a new government -- easily won his. Voter turnout was 64
percent, or 4,815 of 7,517 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third election since 1994 for Anguilla -- an island of
10,000 people located about 150 miles east of Puerto Rico -- which
has been mired in a yearlong political impasse that has frustrated
London.
</P>
<P>
   The island, which depends heavily on upscale tourism, had
elected a coalition government in March 1999 that quickly crumbled
in a dispute between Hughes and Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks left Hughes' Anguilla United Movement and joined the rival
Anguilla Democratic Party United Front. That cut Hughes' party's
seats from four to three. Opposition members boycotted the assembly
and prevented it from meeting, forcing Hughes to call early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Anguilla's political deadlock has exasperated officials in
Britain, while local residents complained officials did little to
create jobs or respond to a London proposal that would change the
relationship between Britain and its territories.
</P>
<P>
   Before their split, Hughes and Banks had negotiated a deal with
Beal Aerospace, a U.S. company, to build a commercial rocket launch
pad on Anguilla's Sombrero Island. The deal could be worth $6
million annually to Anguilla's economy -- roughly a fifth of its
budget. Development awaits regulatory approval from London.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still committed to see it through,'' Beal spokesman Wade
Gates said Friday. ''We are perhaps frustrated by the length of
time to get the project rolling, but we are still moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Guyana also is negotiating with Beal for a similar launch
facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0237 </TRAILER>
