<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Seeks to Postpone Nuclear Suit  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fired nuclear weapons scientist's civil
lawsuit against the government should be postponed until after his
criminal trial on charges of mishandling classified data, the
Justice Department argues.
</P>
<P>
   Former Los Alamos National Laboratory scientist Wen Ho Lee filed
the civil suit 10 days after his indictment last December in order
''to interfere with a pending criminal case against him by
attacking the validity of his indictment,'' the government argued
in a motion for delay filed Friday with U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Lee pleaded innocent, and his criminal trial is to begin Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   His civil suit charged that government officials leaked false
and misleading information to reporters to smear him as a spy for
China before the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The department argued that courts have long held that the
validity of a criminal indictment should be determined by the court
hearing the criminal case, in this case the U.S. District court in
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''Allowing him to proceed with his civil case will interfere
with the prosecution of the criminal case,'' the government added.
It noted that plaintiffs in civil lawsuits have much more freedom
to learn their opponent's evidence through depositions than do
defendants in federal criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any effort to depose government officials familiar with the
Lee investigations, such as FBI agents or Department of Energy
officials -- some of whom are potential trial witnesses -- or
Department of Justice officials working on the case, including
prosecutors, would ... interfere with the government's ongoing work
on the investigation and prosecution,'' the department said.
</P>
<P>
   When the lawsuit was filed, Lee's attorney Brian Sun said it
would allow Lee's lawyers to gather records and testimony about the
investigation and officials' contacts with reporters. ''This
lawsuit is designed to ferret out and identify those folks who
leaked confidential and personal information about Wen Ho and (his
wife) Sylvia Lee to the press,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department argued that postponing the lawsuit would
not prevent the Lees from pursuing their claims but only
temporarily delay them ''while a greater public interest is served
in the pursuit of an extraordinarily significant criminal
proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Dec. 10, in a 59-count indictment in Albuquerque, N.M., Lee
was charged with downloading to an unsecure computer highly
classified data on atomic weapons research, design and testing. The
government charged that he also put the data, with all the
information needed to build a functional hydrogen bomb, on portable
tapes, seven of which remain unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was not charged with spying for China or any foreign
government, but some of the criminal charges alleged his conduct
was done with intent to injure the United States or aid a foreign
power.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's suit accuses the FBI and the Justice and Energy
Departments of violating the Privacy Act by releasing details such
as Lee's job history, his travels to Asia and allegations that he
failed a lie-detector test. The leaks created a ''trial-by-media
atmosphere'' that led to Lee's being charged with improper handling
of classified information, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department told the court that Lee's attorneys
indicated they would likely oppose delaying the civil suit but
wanted to read the government's arguments before responding.
</P>
<P>
   Lee remains held without bail in New Mexico. His wife, a U.S.
citizen born in China who retired from Los Alamos in 1995, has not
been charged with a crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0237 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Assails Gay Marriage Ban  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP ) -- President Clinton is urging voters in
California to reject a ban on gay marriages, saying it is
unnecessary because no state currently honors such unions.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a Democratic fund-raiser in San Francisco on Friday
night, the president said Proposition 22, which would bar
California from recognizing same-sex marriages should they become
legal in any other state, would have ''no practical effect
whatever'' except to divert attention from other, more serious
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a solution in search of a problem that isn't there,''
Clinton said during a reception for Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
''So people are being asked to vote on this to get everybody in a
white heat and to divide people.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception was one of three events headlined by Clinton as
part of a weekend of fund-raisers that raked in $1.6 million for
Democrats. Today, the president was taking a break to spend time
with his daughter, Chelsea, a student at Stanford University,
before traveling to Los Angeles for more fund-raising. He was
finishing his travels Sunday at a civil rights commemoration in
Selma, Ala., before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who is not seeking office, Clinton offered abundant
advice to voters in Tuesday's primary here, a state that supported
him in 1996 and is pivotal to the fortunes of Vice President Al
Gore in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't vote in this primary, but I hope you'll vote,'' he
said. ''You've got a big ballot. You'll have an opportunity to vote
for things that will affect your future and to send a signal where
California is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton curried support for Proposition 26, which would allow
school districts to use property taxes to repay loans for school
construction and renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll build people up,'' Clinton said. ''We've got, already,
untold numbers of kids in schools that are either overcrowded or
tumbling down. ... You need to get all the roadblocks out of your
way to building your children's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the occasion to offer his first public comment
on the Amadou Diallo case, saying he believes the West African
immigrant's race was a factor in his shooting by four white New
York City policemen.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Diallo's parents and black activists pressed
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder to have the Justice Department
pursue civil rights charges against the officers acquitted of
killing Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't pretend for a moment to second-guess the jury,''
Clinton said. ''But I know most people in America of all races
believe that if it had been a young white man in a young all-white
neighborhood, it probably wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton quickly added, ''That doesn't mean they (the
officers) were guilty under criminal law.''
</P>
<P>
   The president began a marathon day at an Aspen Institute forum
in the heart of Silicon Valley, where he challenged online
companies to strengthen consumer privacy safeguards. He also
ordered government agencies to evaluate the security of their own
Web sites and appealed to high-tech firms to work with him to
spread the prosperity that this new economy is creating.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast visit gave Clinton a chance to dabble in politics
just days before California -- the largest electoral state -- votes
chooses Republican and Democrat nominees to succeed him on Super
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Clinton attended two events to raise $600,000
for Feinstein's re-election campaign and the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, as well as a $400,000 Democratic National
Committee dinner. Tonight, he was the featured guest at two DNC
events in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He seized the chance to tout Feinstein as a possible running
mate for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she is immensely talented and would be good at
anything,'' Clinton said. ''But, this is a decision that the vice
president should make after he wins the nomination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0243 </TRAILER>
