<HEADLINE> Seven N. Koreans Defect to S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Seven North Koreans defected to the
South on Saturday after escaping their hunger-stricken communist
homeland, the Seoul government's main spy agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Intelligence Service said the North Koreans, from
two families, had first sought political asylum at a South Korean
diplomatic mission in a third country that the agency refused to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified country assisted South Korean diplomats in
bringing the defectors to Seoul, the spy agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven included a 55-year-old pharmacist, his wife and three
children who had fled communist North Korea between 1998 and 1999,
the spy agency said.
</P>
<P>
   A 36-year-old woman, who had lived in Japan before emigrating to
North Korea, also defected with her 14-year-old son, the agency
said. It gave no further details.
</P>
<P>
   More than 460 North Koreans have defected to South Korea since
1994, about one-third of them last year. Most came through China.
Many have complained of hunger in their homeland, which has
experienced severe drought and famine in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
