<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five dead in Bronx killing spree  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A murder spree in a quiet Bronx neighborhood has
left four family members and a fifth person dead, leaving police
with their hands full with investigating what prompted the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said the victims were part of a large extended family
that had moved to the city from Puerto Rico. Their bodies were
found in three different locations.
</P>
<P>
   The first killing occurred in the Parkside Houses on Olinville
Avenue, where 39-year-old Evelyn Santos was found late Thursday
evening. She had been fatally shot and stabbed inside an elevator,
said Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police efforts to notify Santos' next-of-kin brought them to the
house of Evelyn's sister, where they made another gruesome
discovery. Inside a two-story home on Radcliff Avenue, about 10
blocks away from the first crime scene, police found Evelyn's
30-year-old sister Denise Santos, slashed to death early Friday,
Commissioner Howard Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Police then returned to another apartment in the Parkside Houses
to locate other family members, when, at 7:30 a.m. Friday, they
found the bodies of the brother of the slain sisters, Denise
Santos' fiancDe and a 14-year-old nephew of the sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The two adult victims -- Eduardo Santos, 34, and Irvine Aguilar,
33 -- were shot and stabbed to death. The nephew, Ishmael Santos,
had been fatally stabbed, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the times of death had yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Police were investigating the case as a quintuple homicide. It
wasn't clear whether the murders were committed by one or more
people.
</P>
<P>
   Police had made no arrests by early today.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some leads but no identification of suspects at this
point,'' Safir said, adding that there was no sign of forced entry
at any of the crime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Police in the Bronx neighborhood where the killings happened
handed out fliers asking for help in locating the killer or
killers.
</P>
<P>
   One officer remarked after the police news conference that
Friday's killings bore a striking resemblance to the ''Palm Sunday
Massacre,'' a slaying of ten people-- including eight children-- in
the East New York section of Brooklyn in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Thomas, of the Bronx, was sentenced to a total of
250 years in prison for those slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The NYPD offered a $10,000 reward for information leading to the
arrest and conviction of any suspects involved in Friday's
killings. Anyone with information about the murders was asked to
call police at 1-800-577-TIPS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 0416 </TRAILER>
