<DOCNO> APW20000304.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Shield Tobacco Cos.  </HEADLINE>
By BOB LEWIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- State lawmakers have passed a bill
protecting companies' assets in Virginia, a measure that would
shield tobacco giants such as Philip Morris from a potential
multibillion dollar judgment in a Florida lawsuit filed by ailing
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which Gov. Jim Gilmore is expected to sign,
caps bonds required to appeal punitive damages judgments at $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, which is based in New York but operates the
world's largest cigarette plant in Richmond, is among five tobacco
companies in a class-action lawsuit in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   All could face billions of dollars in damages if they lose,
forcing the companies to post billions of dollars in cash or assets
as bond while the judgment is appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates within the industry have placed the possible punitive
damages from the lawsuit brought on behalf of Florida smokers as
high as $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed the House of Delegates 98-0 and the Senate
33-6 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore persuaded Del. Eric Cantor, a fellow Republican, to
introduce the bill last month. The bill never mentions Philip
Morris or the word ''tobacco,'' and Cantor said Philip Morris was
never mentioned to him in regard to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The link to Philip Morris was drawn in a story published by The
Virginian-Pilot of Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not characterizing it as a Philip Morris bill,'' Cantor
said. ''This allows for a defendant in a lawsuit to avail itself
fully to the appeals process. No entity in the United States could
withstand a $300 billion appeal bond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 0513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Louisville Mayor Fires Police Chief  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CHAMBERS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. -- Police officers and supporters marched on City
Hall to protest Mayor Dave Armstrong's firing of the police chief
who approved awards for two officers involved in the shooting of an
unarmed 18-year-old black man.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of supporters on Friday, wearing T-shirts that read
''Armstrong's Wrong,'' called on the mayor to step down, saying
Thursday's firing of Chief Gene Sherrard was motivated by a vocal
minority.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anyone needs to be removed from office it's not the chief
of police,'' said Rick McCubbin, president of the local Fraternal
Order of Police lodge. McCubbin met with Armstrong behind closed
doors following the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong fired Sherrard after the chief approved awards
honoring officers Chris Horn and Paul Kinkade for their role in an
incident in which an unarmed black man was fatally shot. Horn and
Kinkade, who are white, were awarded the Exceptional Valor Award at
a ceremony Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Horn and Kinkade shot Desmond Rudolph on May 13 as he was
attempting to flee in a stolen vehicle that had become stuck in an
alley. Police fired 22 rounds into the vehicle, saying they feared
Rudolph was going to run them down.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph died four days later, and his death sparked outrage in
the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Sherrard violated his trust by quietly approving
the awards a month earlier amid a grand jury investigation and an
internal probe.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury found no criminal wrongdoing but the internal
probe cited several errors by police before and after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Police complained that Armstrong caved to political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who met with union officials and black leaders
following the rally, said despite the turnout of hundreds at the
pro-police rally, community support is on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's one person the chief has to make happy and that's the
elected representative of the people ... and that did not take
place. And so I removed him. It's not complicated,'' Armstrong
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
