<HEADLINE> Guinea Bissau Exile May Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Guinea-Bissau's exiled president, who
was deposed in a military coup last year, said he is willing to
return to his West African country to stand trial on charges of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Saturday in the Portuguese daily 24
Horas, Joao Bernardo Vieira, who lives under political asylum in
Portugal, said he would return home if he could choose his lawyers
and have international observers witness the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira, blamed by much of the population for the country's
economic hardship during his 19-year rule, suggested setting up an
independent commission to investigate alleged political and
financial crimes in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
   The commission should ''find out exactly what happened in
Guinea-Bissau,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The military leaders who overthrew Vieira allowed him to leave
for exile in Portugal last June after he pledged to return to face
trial in connection with alleged arms deals with separatist rebels
in the Senegalese province of Casamance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Guinea Bissau Attorney General Amine Saad asked
Portugal to revoke Vieira's political asylum after a probe into
alleged politically motivated killings under his rule. The
allegations included the 1986 execution of the leaders of a coup
attempt against Vieira.
</P>
<P>
   Saad opened the investigation after a breakaway military faction
deposed Vieira in May last year, concluding an 11-month conflict in
the tiny country wedged between Senegal and the Republic of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira came to power in a 1980 coup and was reinstated in the
country's first democratic elections in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
