<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Denies Rebuke for Campaigning  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN IAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Acting President Vladimir Putin's press service on
Saturday denied reports that he was rebuked by Russia's election
commission for kicking off his presidential campaign early in
violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's campaign headquarters press service issued a statement
that said the acting president ''never got any official warnings
from the Central Election Commission for any violations in the
course of the election campaign whatsoever, much less for a 'false
start''' of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Segodnya reported Saturday that Putin had violated
election law by campaigning before Feb. 25 -- the first day
campaigning was allowed in the Russian press.
</P>
<P>
   ''One warning to the candidate Putin in connection with
jump-starting the campaign was already made by the Central Election
Commission,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's campaign press service said his open letter to
voters ''was published on Feb. 25 of this year, that is, on the day
of the official start of the election campaign in the media,'' the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, as the incumbent, has been able to camouflage campaigning
as state business, visiting factories, state farms, hospitals and
military units with plenty of TV cameras to record his encounters
with local residents.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Russia's March 26 presidential election hit the
airwaves Friday, the first day when candidates could take advantage
of free ad time on Russian TV and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The five-minute spots, and a series of televised, four-candidate
debates starting next week, are intended to give all 11 candidates
an equal shot at reaching Russia's far-flung voters.
</P>
<P>
   Russian media reported Saturday that Putin had no need of
advertising, and would turn down the opportunity for free time.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Izvestia said, ''the refusal of commercials is a
commercial itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's press service said that the fuss over whether or not he
takes free air time, reports that he did not declare all of his
property or that he jump-started his campaign were links in a
chain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The goal here is simple and understood: to shake the faith of
the voters in the honesty and decency of the candidate,'' the
statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
