<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coloring Book Helps Kids Stop Abuse  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MacDONALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- The letter was just 16 words, printed in a
scared child's scrawl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot call you but I can write,'' it said. ''I'm being
abused of my stepfather. Please help.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter arrived with a Texas postmark at the Rape and Abuse
Crisis Center in Fargo in 1989, and its words seared in center
worker Beth Haseltine's memory.
</P>
<P>
   She later learned that the writer was 7, a second-grader who had
found the center's address inside the cover of a coloring book
called ''Red Flag-Green Flag People,'' part of a sexual abuse
awareness program to help youngsters distinguish inappropriate
touching.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so scared for her,'' recalled Haseltine, now the
non-profit center's director. ''We had no idea who this little girl
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff members eventually were able to track the child down, and
the abuser was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   For Haseltine and others, it is a vivid reminder of the
importance of a coloring book that is now 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Red Flag-Green Flag has grown from a program with its creators
struggling to get the book into a single school in Dilworth, Minn.,
to one recognized across the United States and in 63 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Former center employee Joy Williams saw a need to teach children
about sexual abuse, but she wanted to do it in a way that wouldn't
frighten them. She also wanted them to have the skills to recognize
harmful situations and the self-confidence to speak up.
</P>
<P>
   The coloring book she created teaches children about
''red-flag'' and ''green-flag'' touches. A green-flag touch is one
that makes you feel happy and safe, like a hug from your mother, it
says. A red-flag touch makes you feel scared, confused or
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The book also helps youngsters identify their ''helpers,''
adults such as nurses, their own parents or police officers to whom
they can turn if they experience a red-flag touch, either by a
stranger or even a family member.
</P>
<P>
   The center has countless examples of children who have stepped
forward to report abuse after lessons taught with crayons, coloring
books and chants of, ''Say no, get away, tell a helper!''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to answer how many times a child averted a dangerous
situation because we gave them the knowledge and skills to prevent
it,'' said Carmen Collins, a spokeswoman for Red Flag-Green Flag.
''But that's the real goal of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar programs have been developed, but Red Flag-Green Flag is
considered by many counselors, law enforcement officers and
educators as the premier program of its kind for children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's so accepted because it's very non-threatening,''
said Susan Kamm, coordinator of ''Safe Kids,'' a Grand Rapids,
Mich., program that has used Red Flag-Green Flag materials in its
lessons for six years. ''It's presented in a format that children
understand. It's basic.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a 7-year-old Grand Rapids girl was approached by a man
who tried to lure her into his car. She dropped her backpack and
ran away screaming, something she said she learned to do in Kamm's
program the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   There was resistance to the book at first, said Greg Diehl, Red
Flag-Green Flag's marketing and sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents saw it as an effort to introduce sex education in
grade school, he said. Others believed the program would be too
unsettling for children in the second or third grade.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we first started, it was pretty controversial,'' said
Dave Andersen, then a youth intervention officer with the Moorhead,
Minn., police department. ''There was some misunderstanding about
what we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, parents and school administrators in neighboring
Dilworth, Minn., agreed to try it. Andersen presented the first
class to third graders, and it quickly spread.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've reached every third-grader in the county since 1980. How
many kids that is, I don't know. But it's obviously in the
thousands,'' said Anderson, now assistant police chief.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ''Red Flag-Green Flag People'' spawned an entire
line of educational materials for children about abuse. The center
now publishes more than a dozen story books and coloring books,
including one called ''Red Flag-Green Flag: ABCs of Personal
Safety'' for children as young as 3.
</P>
<P>
   The center also developed a line of videos on sexual abuse and
domestic violence, and a therapeutic board game for adult victims
of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   The coloring books cost about $2 per copy. Diehl said the center
usually makes enough on product sales -- 60,000 coloring books last
year -- to pay for their production.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something our board of directors truly believes in,''
Haseltine said. ''It has become a major part of our mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court: part-time workers who are hurt to get full-timebenefits  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Five years ago, Charles Scott got his left
hand caught in a machine at an Oaklyn bowling alley. The hand was
mangled badly enough to require three corrective surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   While recovering over the next two years, Scott was unable to
work for a few months. In 1997, this drove his family into poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court last week ruled that the strange
circumstances that put Scott and his family into an impossible
financial squeeze should never have occurred and shall never occur
again.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling is a sport Scott had enjoyed since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''I grew up in a bowling alley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott was not at Holiday Bowl for recreation on that
Saturday night in October, 1995. A copy-machine repair technician
by day, Scott had a second job as a part-time counter clerk and
bowling machine technician on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked at bowling alleys most of his adult life and still
does.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was on the job at Holiday Bowl when his hand was
mangled in a jammed pin-changing machine, Scott qualified for
workers compensation benefits, which paid a share of his
$208-a-week salary.
</P>
<P>
   And because he qualified for workers compensation benefits, his
full-time employer, Konica Business Machines, denied his claim for
Temporary Disability benefits when he was out of work in 1997
because of the third surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The company had given Scott medical leave after his injury and
two of the surgeries, but by 1997 it had been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that for several months he had to support his
family on $146 a week -- a fifth of his ordinary income.
</P>
<P>
   His family was pressed into poverty. His wife had to apply for
food stamps to feed their two children. They could have faced
homelessness had their apartment landlord in Saddle Brook not given
them a few months' leeway.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very bad times,'' Scott said. ''I didn't know if I
would be able to continue to work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We did without a lot,'' said Carolyn Scott, his wife. ''The
kids had to wait a little longer for summer clothes. Thank God we
had good landlords.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the temporary disability law in place since 1948,
Konica was on solid legal ground.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Paul Schwartz said there have been thousands of cases
in which workers who are injured in side jobs were routinely denied
disability benefits by their full-time employers.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said someone with a case like Scott's has never
succeeded with an appeal, and his case was no different. The Labor
Department's Board of Review turned him down on the grounds that
since he was getting payments already from Holiday Bowl, he was not
entitled to duplicate benefits from Konica. The fact that the
Holiday Bowl benefits covered only 20 percent of his usual income
was not a factor in judging the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday ruled Konica should have honored
Scott's disability claim because it does not matter where he was
hurt. The court ordered Konica to pay him retroactive benefits of
about $4,500.
</P>
<P>
   In so ruling, the court fundamentally changed disability law
that had been in place 52 years, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took the case to make it clear that this was not the
intent of the Legislature,'' Schwartz said. ''Good cases can make
good law, and this was a perfect case. I could have picked a school
child and they could have won this argument.''
</P>
<P>
   The ironies in Scott's case were profound.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been injured mowing his lawn, repairing his car or
walking to his second job, Konica would have granted his claim for
temporary disability payments. Had he been bowling at Holiday Bowl
when he was hurt, Konica would have paid.
</P>
<P>
   But because he was working at Holiday Bowl at the time of the
injury, the claim was denied.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this day and age, a lot of people work more than one job.
There was a time I had three jobs,'' Scott said. ''I don't think
the law was taking that into account back in 1948.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who handled Scott's case for free, said the legal
defect should have been corrected years ago, but it was not the
sort of case lawyers were willing to bring to the appellate courts
because of the small sums involved.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I billed him $200 an hour for my work, I would be taking
all of his money and he would owe me money. This (case) was never
going to make anybody any money,'' Schwarz said. ''I took it up
because it was the right thing to do and it affects a lot of people
like Charles Scott, who are all our base clients, people who are
hurt on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than write its own opinion, the unanimous court adopted
the appellate division ruling handled down last April by Judge
Edwin Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can find neither logical support nor empirical evidence
that the Legislature intended to deprive a worker who pays
deductions for temporary disability benefits from obtaining those
benefits to compensate him for the loss of income at his full-time
employment merely because his injury occurred at a second or
part-time job taken to supplement that income,'' Stern wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
