<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank cries foul over state ATM fee report  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Forgive Valley National Bank officials for
bristling at the notion that they charge among the highest ATM fees
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That is, after all, what it says in the state's new Consumer
Guide to Bank Fees.
</P>
<P>
   What the guide does not say is that the bank charges $2 at only
nine of its machines. At the bank's other 111 machines in northern
New Jersey, the fee is $1.50 per transaction, about what many other
banks in the state charge for non-customers.
</P>
<P>
   It also fails to note that 50 cents of the fee at those nine
machines goes to state coffers. That's because those machines are
located at the Meadowlands and Monmouth Park racetracks, and the
bank pays the state to lease space at the state-operated tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman released the guide with much fanfare at a
news conference last week. The purpose of the guide is to educate
consumers about less expensive options in the banking industry, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid was that the guide may also steer customers away
from banks that charge higher fees. According to the guide, one
such bank is Valley National.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone is aware that this is an extremely sensitive issue,''
said bank lobbyist Joe Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   It was misleading for the state to label the bank fees $2 across
the board, especially when the state gets a piece of the action, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd venture to say that a majority of our customers do not use
ATMs at the racetrack,'' Orlando said. ''The old woman who lives in
Wayne sees an article that says our ATM fee $2, but unless she has
a problem with the ponies, I don't think that's accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   State Banking and Insurance spokesman Bill Heine said the state
stands by its report.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the bank choses to pass that expense onto its customers,
that's the kind of information consumers need to know. That's why
we put it in the guide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heine said the state did place a footnote next to the $2
notation for Valley National Bank, explaining that its fees vary.
</P>
<P>
   ''How many people read footnotes?'' asked Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials did not volunteer specifics when filling out the
state questionnaire; they merely wrote that their fees range from
$1.50 to $2 depending on location, Heine countered.
</P>
<P>
   State officials chose to list the higher fee so consumers
wouldn't be surprised if they used one of the Valley National
machines that charges it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Sun National Bank had no apologies for being
one of the other four New Jersey banks the guide says charges
non-customers a $2 ATM fee.
</P>
<P>
   No one complains, said bank spokeswoman Allison Kruse.
</P>
<P>
   At the other two banks that the guides says charges $2, a woman
who answered the telephone at First Morris Bank and Trust declined
comment, and no one returned a phone message left with St. Edmond's
Federal Savings Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
