<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penn Station's clicking, old train board shunted aside  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN M. HUBBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The boxy black sign is holding all of them
captive -- the lovelocked couples, the weary commuters, the students
heading home.
</P>
<P>
   It's afternoon in Penn Station. The day's pace is quickening,
more trains are pulling out. Yet under the departure board at its
center, an attentive stillness dominates a patch of shiny linoleum
as passengers await the sign's message.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Herriott, the station announcer, disrupts the calm with
an upbeat ''All aboard!'' The board's domino rows of white-on-black
letters click through the alphabet before the name and track number
of a departing train appear, and travelers rush to get aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Now the board, too, is departing -- a casualty of increasing rail
traffic in Amtrak's burgeoning Northeast corridor. A gleaming,
digital sign, already hanging nearby, should be switched on
sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's called technological advancement,'' Herriott says,
laughing in the booth where she commands the sign, known as the
''Solari'' from the name of its Italian manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade doesn't faze Herriott -- she'll run the new sign, too
-- except the replacement board can speak. Just how much it will say
is uncertain, but Amtrak officials note that ''All aboard,'' now
Herriot's domain, could be part of its vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to know how many passengers have stood watching
the Solari since 1966, when it replaced an older, similar sign. But
500,000 people pass through Penn Station each day, many departing
on the 1,000 daily trains.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the sign's disappearance will mean another bit of the
past gone, like replacing ham and eggs in Carolina with a breakfast
biscuit sealed in cellophane.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of mesmerizing to watch the letters click to their
next destination,'' said Joe Mitchell, 33, waiting to leave for
Wilmington, Del. ''It's certainly an impression I get every time I
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing nearby as the Solari whirred above, Vanessa Pagan, 21,
a Rutgers University student, said she likes ''the noise it makes,
and trying to decide what's going on next.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When I saw that they were making something new -- well, I don't
know,'' Pagan said. New Yorkers, she said, have ''the subway sound,
you have the bus sound -- and you have that sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the frequent, near-musical clicks are themselves testimony
for change.
</P>
<P>
   With trains leaving more quickly than the Solari can display
them, the board is ''starting to get past its lifetime,'' said John
Roseen, Amtrak's manager of customer service. ''When we get into
the rush hour, we start running out of room on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The new, $300,000 digital board can display 16 trains at once,
plus service announcements, all in big, colored letters. The Solari
shows only eight trains.
</P>
<P>
   Other Solaris remain in use elsewhere, including Boston station.
Roseen isn't sure where the Penn Station sign is headed -- maybe
another station, a museum, a back lot.
</P>
<P>
   Some Penn Station workers see the Solari as part of their role
in life, a symbol that train travel is somehow more personal, more
human.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are everything here, from psychiatrists to information
people to doctors,'' said Karen Robinson, an Amtrak employee for 21
years. ''The whole feeling of the station is changing, and the
board is something that is going along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Herriott hopes the new, voice-programmable sign won't add to the
colder world she sees hurrying past. One memory sticks with her as
the worst of modern life: A man suffered a heart attack by the
board, and impatient travelers rushed past, some even jumping over
the prone figure.
</P>
<P>
   ''That'd be a bad way to go out -- to die in Penn Station,'' said
Herriott, 44.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Penn Station announcer Daniel Simmons Jr. understands
the personal touch in train travel but says time can't stand still
-- even if it feels that way waiting for a train.
</P>
<P>
   ''Automation -- you can't stop it,'' said Simmons, 73, from his
home in Delran, N.J. Retired since 1994, he still recalls sometimes
getting applause from travelers as he sang out the destinations of
departing trains.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd put more step in their pep,'' he said, ''because I'd be
rappin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons hopes some personality will linger at Penn Station after
the Solari is gone. Not everyone, he said, comes to a train station
just to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to have a little old lady who would get off of work at
eight or nine o'clock and stand there and look at me for a
half-hour, just listening to me,'' he remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then she would throw me a kiss, and say goodnight, and go
home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 1348 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain's Main Guy: A grandpa who would cut your heart out -- andsmile  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Guy Molinari is a small, bespectacled man with a
healthy shock of white hair and a smile that is a tad devilish. He
has a grandfatherly aura that immediately puts people at ease.
</P>
<P>
   But don't mistake the man Republican hopeful John McCain has
chosen for his New York state campaign chairman as an easy mark.
</P>
<P>
   ''That grandfather would cut your heart out and leave it on the
table with that same sweet grandpa smile and demeanor,'' said
William Powers, chairman of the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   And Powers, who has known Molinari for 25 years, considers
himself a friend, despite their recent differences. Powers is
backing Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the GOP race for president.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCain alluded to Molinari's take-no-prisoners political
style, telling reporters at a December news conference: ''There's
no doubt in my mind, anyone who crosses Guy Molinari does so at
great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain laughed when he said it, Molinari's 25-year
political record, including six years as a state assemblyman, nine
in Congress and 10 as Staten Island borough president, backs up
that view.
</P>
<P>
   It surprises no one that the 71-year-old Molinari finds himself
in deep GOP cold storage these days after switching to the McCain
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jay Severin said Molinari has caught the ire
of his own party so many times that if the dictionary had an entry
for the words ''buck the party'' it would simply say: Guy Molinari.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a maverick before being a maverick was cool,'' said
Severin.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's raising the ire of President Ronald Reagan over a
bill to rehire fired air traffic controllers, or crossing party
lines to endorse Democrats, Molinari's ''political derring-do'' --
as Severin calls it -- has repeatedly gotten him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Molinari, who is both conservative and Catholic,
advocated executing doctors who perform late-term abortions. He
also referred to one Democratic candidate for state office as unfit
for office because she was a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Mayor Ed Koch, who clashed frequently with
Molinari when in office, says Molinari is the kind of politician
''who likes to go for the jugular'' and ''throws his weight
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinari's political, pit bull personality comes in large part
from his roots.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from the city's least-populated and most suburban
borough, he has had to fight to get Staten Island's point of view
across in vastly larger -- and mostly Democratic-run -- New York.
</P>
<P>
   And whether its fighting to close the mammoth 3,000-acre Fresh
Kills landfill or presiding over a local spelling bee, he does it
with unmatched passion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people love him out there,'' said Koch. ''He could be
borough president for life'' -- if not for term limits which will
force him out of office at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Koch admits having a grudging respect for his old
adversary. ''He's got political street smarts. He's got courage.
He's got chutzpah,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident last fall when Molinari announced he was
backing McCain. The defection seemed even more treacherous since
Molinari chaired George Bush Sr.'s New York presidential campaign
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, interviewed last week at his Staten Island office,
said it wasn't an easy decision to make. ''In the end, it's gotta
be who you believe in,'' Molinari said, speaking softly, in a voice
that carries just a tinge of New Yawkese.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage rumblings said Molinari was irked at being left out of
an early appearance by Gov. George W. Bush in New York. Others
believe it was the result of a power struggle with aides to Gov.
George Pataki, Bush's state campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said neither is true. ''I had already considered
endorsing McCain and I don't care if anyone believes that or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The fallout led to an anti-Molinari chill that stretched from
Albany -- where his relationship with Pataki has broken down -- to
his own backyard. Molinari had expected some local Republicans he
helped get elected to follow him, but no one did.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Long Island Rep. Peter King, Molinari is the only
well-known state Republican backing McCain. Even his daughter and
son-in-law, ex-Reps. Susan Molinari and Bill Paxton, are Bush
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's fine. I don't have a problem with that,'' Molinari
said. But he said he does have a problem with Bush's people using
arm-twisting to get others not to support McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should be able to back the person they think is right
for the job,'' he said. ''It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP officials deny they've used pressure to block switches to
McCain. But it's hard to deny the Republican chill toward Molinari,
especially after he led a court battle that got McCain on Tuesday's
primary ballot in all 31 districts over state GOP opposition.
</P>
<P>
   One New York Times story about Molinari, headlined ''The
Patriarch as Pariah,'' quoted anonymous Republican sources as
calling him both a hypocrite and a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   ''What it really means is that you're a player,'' Molinari said,
shrugging off the pariah label. ''In a perverse kind of way, I take
it as a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Severin, who hosts a radio talk show and analyzes politics at
NBC's Web site, believes Molinari's battle for McCain ''is probably
the biggest role of the dice for him.'' If he loses, he may have
permanently damaged his Republican powerbase.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain wins in New York, he said Molinari will have the
shiniest shoulders in town ''from the arms of all the Republican
pols who will be draping them around him, reminding him what good
buddies they've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, who was treated for prostate cancer nearly three years
ago and still suffers from a car accident, has been drained by the
political infighting.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of curtailing his involvement in GOP politics, but says
he still expects to campaign for Republican ally Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani in the upcoming U.S. Senate race and to help select his
own successor as borough president.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he says, all he wants to do is play grandpa to
granddaughters, Susan, 3, and Katherine, 1, who live just outside
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But would he give up politics even if McCain won, Molinari is
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vice president,'' he says pointing to himself, joking. But
with the unpredictable Molinari, who knows?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 1349 </TRAILER>
