<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DeGeneres Avoiding Controversy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Comedian Ellen DeGeneres is getting laughs
from some non-controversial subjects these days. Shampoo bottles,
for example. Just who needs those instructions? And why is there an
800 number on the back?
</P>
<P>
   DeGeneres, who came out as a lesbian along with her lead
character on ''Ellen,'' the ABC sitcom canceled two years ago, says
she doesn't want to be viewed as a political symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she gets the biggest response with references to her
sexuality, in her new standup material she's sticking mostly to
observational humor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is, I've saved people's lives,'' DeGeneres told the
Los Angeles Times for Saturday's editions. ''But I'm really just a
comedian. That's all I am. So it's a very awkward place.
Everybody's got so many different expectations of me.''
</P>
<P>
   DeGeneres now has a pilot deal at CBS for a sitcom in which
she'll play the host of a sketch-variety show. She's also working
on an hourlong comedy special for HBO.
</P>
</TEXT>
