<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York GOP primary a test for Pataki team  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- While competing candidates George W. Bush
and John McCain stumped across New York on Saturday, Gov. George
Pataki also has much on the line in Tuesday's ''Super Tuesday''
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is heading up Bush's New York campaign effort, a job that
once seemed like a plum and now has the possibility of turning into
a pumpkin for the New York governor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Pataki and almost all of New York's Republican
Party hierarchy lined up behind the Texas governor, polls showed
Bush running well ahead of every other Republican contender in New
York. That began to change after McCain trumped Bush in New
Hampshire's leadoff primary. Recent polls have McCain running
neck-and-neck with Bush in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Pataki team still appeared confident on Feb. 13 as the
Texas governor officially placed Pataki in charge of the New York
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows New York and how to win,'' Bush said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know our team will reach out to every Republican voter to
deliver New York state for Governor Bush,'' Pataki boasted.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 22, the stakes grew bigger for Pataki as McCain beat
Bush in Michigan despite the support there for the Texas governor
from Gov. John Engler. Like New York, Bush had entrusted the
Michigan race to its governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pataki has a real risk of being Englerized,'' Nelson Warfield,
a Republican operative who helped run Bob Dole's 1996 presidential
campaign and who knows New York politics well, said. ''If he is
seen as losing his state for Bush, that hurts him.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been some talk, mostly from his New York supporters,
of Pataki as a possible running mate for Bush. But that hinges
largely on a demonstration that the New York governor has at least
a chance of delivering his home state to the Republicans in
November. A loss to McCain's forces on Tuesday would do little to
enhance such thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Pataki has been eyeing running for a third term in 2002, a
campaign that could become more difficult in terms of fund raising
and maintaining party unity if a perception of weakness is created.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tuesday's bar is set high for Pataki. In 1996, the New
York Republican organization delivered every delegate at stake in
the primary to Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But that was back when the New York GOP was still riding high.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Democrats turned Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and state
Attorney General Dennis Vacco out of office and last year the party
lost control of the Nassau County legislature, until then a Long
Island bastion of Republicanism.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the New York GOP suffered an embarrassment when it
lost a battle to use the state's arcane election rules to keep
McCain off the ballot. The move served to enhance McCain's
credentials as an insurgent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pataki seemed to be preparing for trouble on
''Super Tuesday,'' which he told reporters would be a ''difficult
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about whether the primary was also a referendum on the
New York GOP, Pataki bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately it comes down to the candidates ... Next Tuesday's
a referendum on George Bush and John McCain,'' Pataki said.
''That's what all elections are.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pataki has had trouble even keeping the New York troops
in line.
</P>
<P>
   While Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari was a leading
New York supporter of former President George Bush and an early
backer of the Texas governor's campaign, the former congressman
switched over late last year to McCain. Molinari now heads up
McCain's New York campaign along with U.S. Rep. Peter King of Long
Island, a Roman Catholic who deserted the younger Bush after his
visit to Bob Jones University where some officials have expressed
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   And, just days ago, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who
has endorsed Bush, went public with his refusal to join a
Pataki-led effort to attack McCain's legislative record as
''anti-New York.'' The mayor, who is running for the U.S. Senate
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, said he admired McCain and looked
upon him as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some people, they want to demand that you get
involved in negative campaigning and they question your loyalty if
you won't do it,'' the mayor said Thursday in a slap at Pataki's
staff.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sent Giuliani a thank-you note.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated
Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
