<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Injured Crew of Brit Ship Rescued  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALDOSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Air Force personnel rescued two people from
a ship hundreds of miles off the Atlantic coast after the men were
injured in an accident that killed a member of their crew.
</P>
<P>
   The two crewmen from the 465-foot, British-flagged petroleum
tanker Johann Schultewere were flown by helicopter Friday night to
a hospital in Hamilton, Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   One tanker crew member had been killed and four injured Thursday
while trying to secure an anchor in rough seas, said Lt. Col. Mike
Korcheck, operations officer for the 41st Rescue Squadron at Moody
Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-foot swells and 40-knot winds had been reported in the
area hundreds of miles east of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Two who were hurt remained on board the tanker and did not
require emergency medical care, said Korcheck.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force sent two helicopters and two C-130 cargo planes to
Bermuda on Thursday after the Coast Guard requested their
assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
