<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breast Cancer-Marrow Link Studied  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A new study that casts doubt on the value of bone
marrow transplants for women with advanced breast cancer found no
difference in the survival rates of women who underwent the
procedure and those who had only chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. cancer officials had announced in early February that a
South African study which suggested positive results from the
transplant treatment was based on falsified data.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, directed from the University of Pennsylvania
Cancer Center, researchers found that among women whose breast
cancer had spread, patients who received bone marrow transplants
and high doses of chemotherapy ''do not survive longer or have a
longer time to progression of the disease'' than patients who have
regular chemotherapy over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were set to be published in the New England Journal
of Medicine on April 13, but the journal released it Friday on its
Web site. The journal made its report available early because of
concern and confusion over the South African study, said Dr. Marcia
Angell, the journal's editor-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 199 patients took part in the latest study. After
three years, the researchers found no significant difference in the
survival of patients getting transplants plus high-dose
chemotherapy and those given only conventional dose chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   A co-author of the study, Dr. John K. Erban, chief of hematology
and oncology at New England Medical Center, said the transplant
treatment might be preferable for some women because it can be
completed in three weeks. He said the conventional regimen takes
two years and ''is unpalatable for some women.''
</P>
<P>
   Erban said it is possible that a small set of patients might
still be found who do better with the transplants.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Marc E. Lippman of the
Lombardi Cancer Center in Washington, said doctors should
reconsider the way they treat women with advanced breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This form of treatment for women with metastatic breast cancer
has been proved to be ineffective and should be abandoned in favor
of well-justified alternative experimental approaches,'' Lippman
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: The New England Journal of Medicine Web site can
be accessed at www.nejm.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
