<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Party Contender Drops Out  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The debate over who should lead Germany's
Christian Democrats out of the worst scandal in the party's history
narrowed Saturday, after one of the leading candidates said he was
dropping out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Ruehe, a former defense minister under ex-Chancellor
Helmut Kohl who had been a contender for party chairman, told the
Welt am Sonntag newspaper in a report to be published Sunday that
he would not vie for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's conservatives have been publicly debating who will
replace Wolfgang Schaeuble as chairman since he announced last
month that he would resign. His resignation came after others in
the party questioned his handling of the scandal involving
off-the-books cash handovers, secret accounts abroad and illegal
financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ruehe was the party's losing candidate last weekend to be
governor of Schleswig-Holstein state. But he still had managed to
pull in a larger percentage of votes there than the Christian
Democrats were getting in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   The two main remaining candidates to head the party are
Secretary-General Angela Merkel, considered the front-runner, and
Kurt Biedenkopf, governor of the eastern state of Saxony. The party
leadership will decide its recommendation March 20, to be voted on
at a Christian Democrat convention in April.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel refused during a local party convention in Berlin on
Saturday to speak about the job, but received a warm reception.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main obstacles to her getting the post also appeared
to be fading.
</P>
<P>
   The arch-conservative sister party to the Christian Democrats,
the Bavaria-only Christian Social Union, had questioned whether
Merkel would turn away the more conservative members of the party.
A former East German, she has liberal views on immigration and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview to be published Sunday in Bild am Sonntag,
Bavarian governor and CSU party leader Edmund Stoiber said his
''advice for a strong anchor from the state level with a governor
in top leadership'' should not be interpreted as reservations
against Merkel's ability.
</P>
<P>
   Ruehe, however, spoke out for Biedenkopf, 70, in making his exit
from the leadership debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Kurt Biedenkopf, the concept of the future will be more
strongly connected than with some who are younger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel, 45, is a Kohl protege, but has been able to distance
herself from the statesman who led the party for 25 years, 16 as
chancellor. Biedenkopf is highly popular in his state for bringing
in outside investment and making it the most prosperous in the
former east.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a newspaper reported that Kohl plans to make an
appearance in the German parliament for the first time in months.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has withdrawn from public life since the scandal broke
after he admitted accepting up to $1 million in donations from
sources he has refused to name, and he hasn't taken his parliament
seat since Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Leipziger Volkszeitung reported Saturday that Kohl plans to
return to the Bundestag on March 17 for a ceremony marking the 10th
anniversary of the vote that set the stage for Germany's
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the embattled government of Hesse state survived
a test of confidence after the Free Democrat Party there voted to
stay in the ruling coalition with the Christian Democrats and not
demand the governor resign. Roland Koch has come under fire for
acknowledging that $750,000 in campaign money he declared as a loan
actually came from a state party slush fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1502 </TRAILER>
