<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two gun threats cause scares at schools  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Two separate threats of deadly gun violence
involving students were promptly defused Friday, school officials
and police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, a kindergarten student in Sayreville told
another student that he would put a gun in the 6-year-old boy's
mouth and pull the trigger, officials at Wilson Elementary School
said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother, Gina Swanson, told school officials of the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The threat was taken seriously by officials but later ''we
determined the child was not a threat,'' said Georgia Bauman, the
school's principal. Bauman said the incident wasn't reported to
borough police and that school disciplinary action was taken
against the child.
</P>
<P>
   Bauman said she couldn't say what specific action was being
taken. The school's disciplinary policy includes possible
suspension for such activities.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson, meantime, said her son was scared when he reported the
threat but added, ''I'm proud of him, that he came home and told
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second incident, police say a 16-year-old student
threatened a teacher with a fake gun at Irvington High School.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a cheap plastic gun, but it looked pretty real,'' said
Irvington Police Chief Steven Palamara.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who wasn't identified because of her age, was taken
into custody, charged with juvenile delinquency and taken to the
Essex County Youth House.
</P>
<P>
   About ten police officers went to the school at about 11 a.m.
Friday after school officials called police and said a student had
pointed a gun at a teacher. Police later found the fake gun using
information given by students.
</P>
</TEXT>
