<HEADLINE> Teachers Shun Pupil for Grisly Work  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAEFORD, N.C. (AP) -- Three English teachers at Hoke High School
are refusing to teach a 16-year-old freshman who was suspended for
writing a paper that portrayed the killings of students and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office said the teachers can refuse
to have Russell Almanza in their classrooms as long as he receives
his English assignments from another certified instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Almanza was suspended Feb. 18 for 10 days after writing an essay
describing a shooting at the school. He portrayed himself as an FBI
agent investigating the shooting and used the names of people he
knew, including English teacher Erica Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't want to scare anyone and just wanted a chance
to be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they really read the story, they could see I'm the good
guy,'' he said. ''I never threatened anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   After an appeal, the suspension was reduced to five days and he
was allowed to return to school on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions of his return was that he be assigned to
another English teacher. He also agreed to receive counseling and
signed a contract promising to behave.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of the ninth-grade English teachers would allow
him in their classrooms. Instead, he was placed in the library
during his English period and he was to be given assignments and
monitored by another teacher, said principal Barry Wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
