<HEADLINE> Fifteen Killed in Algerian Attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Three brutal attacks against civilians
in Algeria have left 15 dead, including 10 members of one family,
local newspapers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The daily Liberte said an armed group killed the 10 family
members on Thursday night in Larbaa, 12 miles east of the capital
Algiers. The group used explosives to force their way into the
house, and then shot their victims or killed them with knives.
</P>
<P>
   Another paper, Le Matin, said an armed group killed three
villagers and injured three others Wednesday night in Gheraibiya, a
small town 43 miles south of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
   Two more people were killed Thursday when they were stopped at a
roadblock set up near Tipaza, west of Algiers, by an armed group of
Islamic militants. The victims' throats were cut and the bodies
burned, Le Matin reported.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a peace drive by President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, Islamic
insurgents continue to carry out attacks on civilians in this North
African nation. They have been fighting since 1992, when the army
canceled legislative elections that the now-outlawed Islamic
Salvation Front was poised to win.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people have been killed in the eight years of
fighting since then.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of Bouteflika's peace plan offered partial amnesty
to Muslim rebels who surrendered by Jan. 13. Bouteflika said more
than 6,000 insurgents had accepted the offer, and promised ''a
fight without mercy'' for those who refused.
</P>
<P>
   Although some groups have turned themselves in and disbanded,
the most radical Armed Islamic Group has not officially accepted
the peace plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
