<HEADLINE> Foreign Sailors Ordered Repatriated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- U.S. Immigration officials have ordered the
repatriation of foreign sailors who have been stranded since their
freighter was damaged by Hurricane Georges in the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Star was towed into Tampa after the hurricane, and
the Coast Guard ordered the ship held until repairs made it
seaworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a succession of foreign crew members have been
stranded here, some for more than a year, unpaid, unable to leave
the ship. They lived without heat or air conditioning, a garden
hose their only source of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the fault of the crew,'' said Ron Johnson of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service. ''They were told to come
here and do a job. They had no way of knowing what they were
getting into. But the ship owners knew darn well that ship wasn't
going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS ordered the sailors to be returned home by March 13. If
that deadline isn't met, the INS said it would deport the crew
members and send the bill to the ship owners.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also lifted restrictions that kept six crew members
aboard the Golden Star and five others stuck at a local motel
waiting for back pay and a plane ticket home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The end result is we're going to have 11 Lithuanians who are
pretty happy,'' Johnson said after the orders were issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The men were to collect back pay ranging, in some cases up to
$9,000, from the ship owner, listed in documents as Tamboril
Properties Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
