<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Predicts Three Party Race  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENBELT, (Md.) -- The acrimony dividing the Republican and
Democratic parties creates an opening for ''a fighting three-way
race for the presidency of the United States'' this year,
conservative columnist Patrick Buchanan said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're seeing is a process of the disintegration of those
national parties,'' Buchanan told the Maryland Reform Party, which
awarded the state's 11 delegates to the national nominating
convention to Buchanan. ''We hope to gather together some of those
pieces and put together a plurality in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasty primary battles between Republicans George W. Bush and
John McCain and Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley have permanently
weakened the major parties, he said. By default, Buchanan said,
that situation strengthens the third party, despite its own
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing a process of de-alignment, which I think
ultimately is going to result in a realignment of the two
parties,'' Buchanan said. ''One national party will emerge with the
ideas we represent...and we will take over parts of both parties
that share these views and values.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of his ''peasants with pitchforks'' taking over the
political process is a familiar refrain for Buchanan, who left the
GOP in October after two White House bids in which he vowed to
steer the party away from free trade and moderate social positions
only to lose in Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Buchanan this year bolted the GOP in part
because he realized that his candidacy and the arguments in his
controversial book, ''A Republic, Not an Empire,'' would get lost
in the flood of Republican candidates and their memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party, still roiling over its direction, its leaders
and the whereabouts of $2.5 million in federal convention funding,
provides Buchanan a bullhorn almost all to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Through it, he plans to tone down his rhetoric on issues that
critics have branded extremist and that could alienate core Reform
Party constituencies, especially on social issues, according to
National Chairman Pat Choate.
</P>
<P>
   ''He talks less about abortion, for example,'' Choate said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the continuing unrest in the Reform Party was the
decision by the Minnesota Reform Party Saturday to separate
officially from the national party. The Minnesota group reclaimed
the name Independence Party and gave itself the slogan ''socially
inclusive, fiscally responsible.'' The state party followed the
lead of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, who urged that it take the
step as he left the Reform Party last month.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the moves were upset with the unrest in the
national party and concerned about the impact of potential Reform
Party presidential nominee Buchanan's conservative views. Opponents
of the decision to break free wanted to stay and fight for the
future of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Now Buchanan uses softer rhetoric. For example, on Saturday he
called his opposition to free trade agreements ''economic
patriotism,'' and his opposition to the Clinton administration's
don't-ask-don't-tell policy ''social experiments in the military.''
On issues like abortion, Buchanan said he would trumpet ''a
traditionalism on social issues.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue on which Buchanan believes Reform Party members can
agree is an opposition to free trade agreements. Choate said
Buchanan will ride that issue heavily as the Clinton administration
raises its pressure on Congress to normalize China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan plans to turn up the volume on his campaign as the
primary battles fade. If upcoming primaries in more than a dozen
big states kill off the candidacies of Bradley and McCain, Buchanan
will have his opening at a time when the surviving major party
candidates are broke and tired, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The winter campaigning is about over and we're just starting
spring training,'' Buchanan told about 80 people gathered at the
Marriott here.
</P>
<P>
   ''The press that likes Bradley and loves McCain'' will look for
a better story than ''a boring battle between Bush and Gore,''
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to take aim especially at Bush, his former fellow
Republican, for being ''basically a nice fellow, but clueless'' on
foreign policy issues, an area of expertise for Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think they've shed a lot of blood in that Republican
Party lately,'' Buchanan said. ''But you wait 'til we get ahold of
old W.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1650 </TRAILER>
