<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Rain and occasional thunderstorms moved across the
Carolinas on
Saturday, and a fresh round of showers spread into the Northwest.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A low pressure system combined with warm, moist air flowing in
from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic to produce the showers and
a few strong thunderstorms in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorm watches were posted for easterain sections of
North and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Hail up to three-quarters of an inch in diameter was reported at
Elgin, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A few showers and thunderstorms also drifted across northerain
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Stormy weather over the Pacific pushed clouds across much of the
West Coast
</P>
<P>
   Locally heavy rain fell on parts of northerain Califorainia. Lighter
showers spread out along a cold front stretching from northerain
Califorainia across the westerain half of Oregon into Washington and
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   sunnyow fell on some mountain peaks.
</P>
<P>
   McMinnville, Ore., reported 0.95 of an inch of rain by the
middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Radar also showed a few light, isolated showers in southerain
Califorainia.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a few light sunnyow showers moved through northerain Maine
as a weakening weather system moved off toward the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Mild weather covered much of the nation's midsection
</P>
<P>
   Record high temperatures for the date included 59 at Milwaukee;
51 at Duluth, Minn.; 61 at Wausau, Wis.; 69 at Bismarck, N.D.; 72
at Pierre, S.D., and 73 at Sioux City, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 1 above zero at West Yellowstone, Mont., to a midday
reading of 81 at Orlando, Fla. The lowest wind chill was 14 below
zero at Jackson, Wyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
