<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INS Takes Back Once-Deported Man  </HEADLINE>
By BERT WILKINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) -- U.S. immigration officials have taken
back a man deported to Guyana last year, but still have not been
able to confirm his true identity, an embassy official said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Edgar Garfield Gibbons, insists he is American. On
Friday night, he was accompanied by Immigration and Naturalization
Service agents on a commercial flight from Georgetown to New York.
He was then to be transferred to Texas, the state from which he was
deported in April, U.S. Embassy spokesman Vincent Principe said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in this South American nation had pressed the United
States to take Gibbons back after they were unable to find any
record of him. They said they believed his contention that his
identity had been confused with that of a Guyanese-born man in New
Jersey with the same name and a similar birth date.
</P>
<P>
   Now U.S. officials are investigating a theory that the deportee
stole the identity of the Gibbons living in New Jersey, Principe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And so he was stuck with the identity and had to accept his
deportation to Guyana,'' Principe said. ''That is the most likely
theory, but we are still not sure what is his real name and true
identity, but we are getting close.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons was deported after serving one year in a Texas prison on
a drug charge. He insisted he was born in Monroe, La., and grew up
in Houston. But INS officials have not been able to find any record
of him there.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have taken fingerprints from Gibbons and have
been working with Interpol to determine his identity. Until his
identity is clear, Gibbons will remain at a Texas facility,
Principe said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Guyanese Home Affairs Minister Ronald Gajraj
said that if U.S. officials did not act in two weeks then Guyana
would expel Gibbons, whom the government had already declared a
stateless person.
</P>
<P>
   Since his deportation in April, Gibbons had been living in a
Georgetown police station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1706 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rampage After Indian Election  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Furious that their party was dislodged from
power in India's troubled Bihar state, political activists
protested Saturday by ripping up railroad tracks and blocking train
service.
</P>
<P>
   The activists were members of the Rashtriya Janata Dal party, or
RJD. Their rampage came a day after the main opposition -- the
National Democratic Alliance, or NDA, of Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee -- formed a government following elections in the
eastern state.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the protest action, but all trains passing
through Bihar had to halt on their way to or from India's eastern
and northeastern states. The route is crucial for transporting
minerals and food products throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad tracks were damaged in at least four places. Passenger
trains to eastern Calcutta and to the northern capital, New Delhi,
were parked on the tracks all day, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bihar's fractured elections ended with no party taking a
majority. RJD ran the government before the elections. But in a
constitutional convention, state Gov. Vinod Chandra Pandey asked
the NDA to take power and prove a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The state's NDA leader, Nitish Kumar, took over as chief state
minister, replacing RJD leader Rabri Devi. Kumar said police would
crack down on the rioters attacking railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Violent protests are common in Bihar, India's poorest and most
lawless state. The state is wracked by caste clashes and a
rebellion by Maoist groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1708 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo Protesters Want Fed Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calls for action in the death of Amadou Diallo
increased Saturday as the Justice Department continued reviews of
New York City police practices as well as the case of four New York
policemen who shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow police officers, fellow Muslims and even President
Clinton weighed in over the weekend on the case of the West African
immigrant killed in a hail of gunfire by police who say they
mistakenly thought he pulled a gun on them.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, several dozen people, mostly American Muslims,
protested Saturday in front of the Justice Department, saying the
department should file a federal lawsuit against the New York
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened to Amadou Diallo, what has happened to others
... is a pattern of abuse within the New York Police Department
that has been going on for many years,'' Mauri Saalakhan, of the
human rights group Peace and Justice Foundation, told a noon rally
of about 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''They should spend the money on a federal suit against the NYPD
and the city of New York for a pattern of civil rights
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a coalition of black law enforcement groups called
for a review of the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want the Justice Department to look into this, to
investigate,'' Charles Billups, head of the Grand Council of
Guardians, said in a press conference on the steps of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   His group represents black members of the NYPD, the state
troopers and law enforcement agencies on Long Island and the
northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has said it already is doing both of
those things. It is reviewing the Diallo case, specifically, as
well as investigating the patterns and practices of the New York
department, a probe expanded to include the Street Crime Unit after
Diallo's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   All four officers in that case were assigned to Street Crimes, a
roving group of plainclothes officers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Diallo's parents and black activists met for almost
two hours with Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder to press for
Justice Department action and to bring attention to the broader
issue of police brutality. Holder made no guarantee that charges
would be sought.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the policemen plan to visit the Justice Department
Monday to argue against civil rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton offered his first public comment on the case
Friday night at a political fund-raiser, saying he believes
Diallo's race was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't pretend for a moment to second-guess the jury,''
Clinton said. ''But I know most people in America of all races
believe that if it had been a young white man in a young all-white
neighborhood, it probably wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers fired 41 shots at Diallo in the early hours of Feb.
4, 1999, as he stood in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building. They testified they fired when Diallo reached for what
they thought was a gun but what turned out to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a jury of eight whites and four blacks acquitted the
officers of all charges, which ranged from second-degree murder to
reckless endangerment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1709 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Pistol Smuggling Goes Awry  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Surgeons operated on a woman who
smuggled an automatic pistol into a high-security prison by
concealing it in her rectum but was unable to remove the gun from
its hiding place.
</P>
<P>
   Tirsa Ruiz slipped the 7.65 mm pistol past security checks at
Bogota's La Picota prison on a visit last week to a suspected
leftist rebel prisoner, local newspapers reported Saturday. But
once inside the prison, she realized the gun was stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming she was pregnant, Ruiz, 43, complained of acute stomach
pains and was taken to a hospital. She stayed there for three days,
the gun firmly lodged inside her.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons finally removed the pistol Wednesday after Ruiz
confessed to the real cause of her discomfort. On Saturday, she was
recovering in the hospital under police guard. She was charged with
illegal weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   Prison guards say visitors have often used body cavities to
smuggle drugs and liquor to inmates since a court ruling last year
banned intimate body searches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1711 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rally at Justice Department demands federal lawsuit against NYPD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calls for action in the death of Amadou Diallo
