<DOCNO> APW20000304.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Cycling Star Abducted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Military troops and police combed the
mountains south of Bogota on Saturday after suspected leftist
rebels kidnapped a national cycling hero -- the second to be
abducted this year.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alberto Herrera, the 1987 Vuelta de Espana champion, was
snatched by seven heavily armed men from his parents' farm near the
town of Fusagasuga, police said. The abduction came a month after
rebels from the National Liberation Army freed cyclist Oliverio
Rincon after keeping him for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera competed several times in the Tour de France and the
Gira de Italia before retiring from cycling.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen -- who cut the farm's telephone cable before abducting
the retired sportsman -- claimed they were guerrillas, but didn't
say which faction they belonged to, Herrera's mother told local
radio news.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels from the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC,
Colombia's largest guerrilla group, maintain a strong presence in
the Andean mountains south of Bogota, and often carry out
abductions for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The National Liberation Army -- called the ELN -- is Colombia's
second largest rebel force with 5,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the military said rebels in western Colombia
kidnapped at least 25 workers from a company that repairs electric
towers.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were en route Friday to repair a tower knocked down
by guerrillas of the National Liberation Army in Guatape, 125 miles
northwest of Bogota, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN opposes the privatization of Isagen, the state electric
company, and has been blamed for many attacks on electrical
transmission towers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1716 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Prosecutor: Trial Is On  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. (AP) -- Scotland's top prosecutor met Saturday
with the families of the victims of the Lockerbie jet bombing to
assure them the case was going to trial, despite the sudden
resignation of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Colin Boyd asked to attend an annual meeting of
Northeast-based families of the victims so he could address their
concerns. He's scheduled to meet with more victims' families and
U.S. officials Monday in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd took over as lead prosecutor after Lord Andrew Hardie
resigned last month to accept a judgeship.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is set to begin May 3 in the Netherlands under
Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Monetti, 57, from Cherry Hill, N.J., listened to Boyd's
assurances, but said Hardie's departure was another blow to the
families.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need the agony and the trial is going to be long
enough as it is,'' said Monetti, whose 20-year-old son Rick died on
the plane. ''I wish it was half over already.''
</P>
<P>
   Libyans Abdel Basset Ali al-Magrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhiman
face charges including murder and conspiracy to murder in the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103. The plane exploded over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in December 1988, killing 259 passengers and 11 people on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintain that the two men were responsible for
placing a suitcase bomb on a flight originating in Malta and having
it transferred onto the Pan Am airliner in London. The men,
employed by the Libyan national airline in Malta, were allegedly
undercover intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd on Saturday said he wouldn't object to the release of a
letter from UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan to Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi, though he pointed out he has no authority to
release the document, which is in the hands of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the victim's families believe the letter indicates that
Gadhafi turned over the two suspects in exchange for protection
from prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
