<HEADLINE> Brit Appoints New Anguilla Leader  </HEADLINE>
By WYCLIFFE RICHARDSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE VALLEY, Anguilla (AP) -- Britain's governor to Anguilla named
Osbourne Fleming as the Caribbean territory's new chief minister
Saturday after his former opposition party won legislative
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, whose coalition won four of seven seats in Friday's
vote, will be sworn in Monday, British Gov. Peter Johnston said in
his statement.
</P>
<P>
   All seven incumbents in the assembly were re-elected -- but
because one of the assembly members had switched political parties,
outgoing Chief Minister Hubert Hughes lost his majority.
</P>
<P>
   Anguilla, which depends heavily on upscale tourism, had elected
a coalition government in March 1999 that quickly crumbled in a
dispute between Hughes and Finance Minister Victor Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks left Hughes' Anguilla United Movement and joined the rival
Anguilla Democratic Party United Front. The defection shrank
Hughes' share of seats in the assembly from four to three.
Opposition members boycotted the assembly and prevented it from
meeting, forcing Hughes to call early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout on the island of 10,000 people was 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Anguilla's political deadlock had exasperated officials in
Britain, while local residents complained officials did little to
create jobs or respond to a London proposal that would change the
relationship between Britain and its territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
