<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Battle As Big Votes Loom
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- In the weekend before Tuesday's 13-state
sweepstakes, Texas Governor George W. Bush campaigned in New York while Arizona
Senator John McCain started in New England, the geography highlighting the
presidential contenders' different strategies as they seek their share of the
613 delegates up for grabs. Polls show McCain leading Bush in some New England
states, so the Arizona senator started his day in Boston before flying to an
event in Portland, Maine. Polls indicate a tight race in New York and McCain was
also making stops in Syracuse and Rochester.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunfire Causes Dozens To Flee Yugoslavia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- An exchange of gunfire in a town just outside
Yugoslavia's border Saturday prompted dozens of ethnic Albanian women and
children to flee across the Kosovo border. The exodus of some 175 people was the
latest push from Dobrasin, a predominantly ethnic Albanian town in eastern
Serbia. Hundreds of people have fled the area in the past two months, streaming
into the closest Kosovo town of Gnjilane, about 30 miles southeast of Kosovo's
provincial capital, Pristina. The area near Dobrasin has been the site of
sporadic clashes between ethnic Albanian guerrillas and Serb police.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dating Ban Lift Stuns Bob Jones Campus
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- The decision at Bob Jones University to lift the ban
on interracial dating stunned both students and the fundamentalist Christian
school's supporters. Speaking on Larry King Live, the school's president, Bob
Jones III, said the extraordinary national scrutiny the school has received
since George W. Bush made a campaign appearance led to the move. Bush appeared
at the school last month and later apologized for failing to criticize the
school's anti-Catholic views and racial policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Survivors Flock to Camps
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Thousands of hungry and thirsty Mozambique flood
victims straggled into makeshift camps Saturday after days of huddling on
rooftops and clinging to trees. As supplies and equipment arrived from around
the world, many survivors gulped down the first meal they had eaten in four or
five days. Authorities estimated that 1 million people in this southeast African
country urgently require food, medicine and shelter. Aid workers expected the
death toll from the disaster to soar into the thousands as floodwaters in
southern Mozambique receded and revealed the twisted mud-covered remains of the
dead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Officials: Israeli Base Attacked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas attacked an Israeli military outpost in
southern Lebanon on Saturday night, wounding an Israeli soldier and prompting
strikes from Israeli warplanes, Lebanese security officials said. The guerrillas
fired rockets at the military base at Beaufort, a centuries-old mountaintop
castle 12 miles north of the Israeli border with commanding views of southern
Lebanon and northern Israel. Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas have killed
seven Israeli soldiers and six pro-Israeli militiamen, including the South
Lebanon Army militia's No. 2 commander, since Jan. 25.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rampage After Indian Election
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Furious that their party was dislodged from power in
India's troubled Bihar state, political activists protested Saturday by ripping
up railroad tracks and blocking train service. The activists were members of the
Rashtriya Janata Dal party, or RJD. Their rampage came a day after the main
opposition -- the National Democratic Alliance, or NDA, of Indian Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee -- formed a government following elections in the eastern
state. Bihar's fractured elections ended with no party taking a majority. But in
a constitutional convention, state Gov. Vinod Chandra Pandey asked the NDA to
take power and prove a majority.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Organic Food Standards To Be Set
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As early as Tuesday the first national standards for
organic food will be announced, expected to take effect this summer. The new
guidelines will spell out for the first time what it means for foods to be
labeled organic. They also will bar the use of genetically engineered crops or
irradiated ingredients in organic foods. Food grown and processed in accordance
with those rules can carry a seal of approval from the Agriculture Department,
agency officials say.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockets Beat Nets 99-92, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Kelvin Cato scored Houston's last four points in regulation
to help force overtime, then added five points in the extra period to push the
Rockets to a 99-92 victory over the New Jersey Nets today. Cato, who had only
two points entering the final three minutes of the game, finished with 11.
Stephon Marbury scored a game high 35, Keith Van Horn added 24 and Kerry Kittles
17 as the Nets lost in Houston for the ninth straight time.
</P>
