<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Rally Held in Ala.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A group that wants the South to secede from the
union staged a Confederate flag-waving rally today, a day before President
Clinton was to lead marchers across a Selma bridge to mark the 35th anniversary
of ''Bloody Sunday'' in the civil rights movement. Bloody Sunday was the day
scores of black voting rights demonstrators were beaten by state troopers and
sheriff's officers as they crossed the Edmund Pettus Bridge on a march to
Montgomery. After today's rally, members of the Southern nationalist
organization signed a ''Declaration of Southern Cultural Independence,''
described as the first step in what they hope is a second secession by the
South.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley Invokes Truman During Speech
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An upbeat Bill Bradley brushed aside long odds facing his
campaign today and spoke of ''a world of possibilities guided by goodness,''
reminding his volunteers that another Missouri native, Harry Truman, defied the
polls to win an election more than 50 years ago. Bradley was accompanied by
former New York City Mayor Ed Koch and actor Harvey Keitel when he met in
Greenwich Village with volunteers. He and his wife, Ernestine, also were holding
a rally on New York's Upper West Side before heading to a ''Democrat Days''
event in Hannibal, Mo.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polish Ambassador Freed in Yemen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Yemeni tribesmen released the Polish ambassador early
Sunday after holding him captive for nearly four days. Krzysztof Suprowicz
arrived Sunday morning at the embassy in the capital San'a, his wife Nina said.
Suprowicz was abducted Wednesday by members of the Yamaneyatain tribe. The
abductors were demanding the Yemeni government free fellow tribesmen arrested
recently in exchange for the diplomat's release.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Survivors Flock to Camps
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Thousands of hungry and thirsty Mozambique flood
victims straggled into makeshift camps Saturday after days of huddling on
rooftops and clinging to trees. As supplies and equipment arrived from around
the world, many survivors gulped down the first meal they had eaten in four or
five days. Aid workers expected the death toll from the disaster to soar into
the thousands as floodwaters in southern Mozambique receded and revealed the
twisted mud-covered remains of the dead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Civil Rights Groups Want LAPD Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A coalition of 49 civil rights groups added its voice
today to the growing chorus of people calling for an independent review of the
widening Los Angeles Police Department corruption scandal. Coalition supporters
included state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, and representatives of Amnesty
International and the American Civil Liberties Union. The scandal, which came to
light last fall, has centered on allegations by former Officer Rafael Perez that
officers in an anti-gang unit operating in the poor, mostly Hispanic Rampart
neighborhood beat, framed and even shot suspects.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World's Population Getting Fatter
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the first time in history, there may be as many people
overweight, 1.1 billion, as underfed, researchers report. Just because people
are gaining weight also does not mean the world is better fed, officials said
Sunday. In some countries there is a growing ''weight gap.'' Well-off minorities
in India, China, Brazil and some other developing nations are growing fat as the
poor go hungry. America and other wealthier countries have the opposite problem:
The richer and better-educated tend to eat right, while the poor often balloon
from a diet of cheap and fatty fast foods.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Playstation Sells Out in Japan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Sony's PlayStation 2 hit stores in Japan on Saturday and sold
out promptly, whisked off by eager fans who spent the night waiting in line to
snap up the video-game machines. Competition for the console was fierce selling
for the equivalent of $370.The PlayStation 2 can play DVD movies and compact
discs, has stereo-quality sound, and can connect the user to the Internet. It
will be available in the United States and Europe in time for the Christmas
shopping season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UCLA Upsets No. 1 Stanford 94-93 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- A wild and controversial UCLA upset of top-ranked
Stanford ended with Bruins coach Steve Lavin hugging a referee and shirtless
UCLA players running back and forth to the locker room in dismay and then
celebration. JaRon Rush, playing his first game after a nine-game suspension,
hit a disputed baseline jumper with 3 seconds remaining in overtime as UCLA
defeated Stanford 94-93 today. Rush, who scored 19 points to lead the Bruins,
grabbed a loose ball under the UCLA basket after a wild scrum during which the
shot clock appeared to expire. Stanford's Casey Jacobsen then missed a desperate
half-court shot, and UCLA ran to its locker room in celebration.
</P>
