<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Ambassador Freed in Yemen  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Yemeni tribesmen released the Polish
ambassador unharmed early Sunday after holding him captive for
nearly four days.
</P>
<P>
   Krzysztof Suprowicz arrived Sunday morning at the embassy in the
capital San'a, his wife Nina said.
</P>
<P>
   Suprowicz was abducted Wednesday by members of the Yamaneyatain
tribe after dropping his wife and daughter off at the dentist in
downtown San'a. The abductors were demanding the Yemeni government
free fellow tribesmen arrested recently in exchange for the
diplomat's release.
</P>
<P>
   An Interior Ministry official said the kidnappers had been given
a midnight deadline to turn over the diplomat or the government
would use force. Officials said he was freed just after midnight
Sunday morning, but gave no details on how the release took place.
</P>
<P>
   ''I confirm he's at the embassy. He's on his way home. I'm
waiting for him,'' Nina Suprowicz told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Suprowicz was the first ambassador to be kidnapped in Yemen,
where tribesmen often kidnap foreigners, including diplomats, to
pressure the government into releasing jailed tribesmen or to
provide money or better services, such as new roads.
</P>
<P>
   Hostages usually are treated as guests and released unharmed.
However, in 1998, four kidnapped tourists were killed in a botched
rescue attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador's release followed a day of roller-coaster
negotiations, which nearly set him free hours earlier. He was being
held in rural areas a few hours drive from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Yemeni Deputy Foreign Minister Abdullah al-Sayeghi had met with
Polish Embassy officials Saturday and it appeared Suprowicz was
about to be released. However, the kidnappers then abruptly called
off their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sources within the tribe who spoke on condition of anonymity
said the kidnappers had taken Suprowicz to a neutral party late
Saturday afternoon with the intent of releasing him. But shortly
after the kidnappers arrived, they changed their minds and decided
to keep the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said without elaborating that the Yamaneyatain tribe
felt the government had broken a promise it had made to the
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   Suprowicz has been living in the impoverished Arab state since
1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Poland's President Aleksander Kwasniewski suggested
Warsaw should reconsider whether maintain a Polish diplomatic
mission in the country because of its poor safety record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1910 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Team Falls Short After Tragedy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The quest by the Brock High School girl's
basketball team to win a state title in honor of their teammates
killed in an automobile crash had captivated their entire
community.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 of the town's 700 residents made the 244-mile trip to
see their team compete Saturday for the Class 2A crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Eagles wanted to win their first state title to honor
the family, friends and teammates who were supposed to be with
them. And they wanted to bring some comfort to a town still
grieving the December 1998 crash that killed four students.
</P>
<P>
   Brock lost the championship 47-35 to Farwell, but the team -- and
its devoted followers -- did not lose their determination or
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel real bad, but we have two more years,'' said Brock
sophomore Emily Osina, whose sister, Lacey, was one of those
killed. ''We will win state the next two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The players dedicated their title run to former teammates Lacey
Osina, Staci Lee and Mandy McWhorter and friend Whitney Welch. Lee
and McWhorter were underclassmen and would have been on this year's
team.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Carter, the driver of the pickup truck that hit the
girls, has been charged with four counts of intoxication
manslaughter. He awaits a March 20 hearing on whether to move the
case to another county.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service marked the one-year anniversary of the
deaths, and an eternal flame burns at the gravesite in the town
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The team's run through the playoffs had been relatively easy.
The starting lineup of four sophomores and a freshman rolled over
defending champion Hughes Springs in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   With the motivation of playing for something deeper, this would
be the year they won state. Ten previous state tournament
appearances had come up short.
</P>
<P>
   Brock fans filled their section of the University of Texas'
Frank Erwin Center 45 minutes before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the publicity surrounding their championship run,
the Brock team smiled and giggled through their pregame
shootaround.
</P>
<P>
   Kaycie Cole's 3-pointer for a 3-0 lead brought the Brock fans to
their feet. And then it got grim. Farwell, the team that was
supposed to be overmatched, hit two quick shots for a 4-3 lead and
never trailed again.
</P>
<P>
   Brock rallied to pull within 39-32 in the fourth quarter but
couldn't sustain the comeback. As the closing seconds ticked off
and the game out of reach, Emily Osina headed to the bench with her
jersey pulled up to her face.
</P>
<P>
   She broke into sobs when she sat down, the Brock fans sitting in
stunned silence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a hurt inside,'' said Doug McWhorter, Mandy McWhorter's
father. ''But I know Mandy, Staci, Lacey and Whitney were with them
today, encouraging them on. We can't say how proud we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The tears eventually stopped and smiles returned to the players'
faces by the time of the trophy presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure they'll beat themselves up for a couple of days. I
know in Emily's case, she really wanted to win for her sister.''
said Brock coach Tony Phillips. ''But this is a strong bunch. They
played their hearts out, so they didn't come up short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 1917 </TRAILER>
