<DOCNO> APW20000304.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush skips '60 Minutes' after CBS agrees to McCain request forequal time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- George W. Bush scrapped a planned interview
on Sunday's ''60 Minutes'' after his Republican presidential rival,
Sen. John McCain, was offered equal time by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides say they contacted the show to suggest a
debate or at least get equal time for their candidate. A CBS
official says the network was interested in offering McCain a
chance to appear on the show anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign had viewed the interview as ''a good
opportunity to speak to a lot of people'' before Tuesday's
13-state, ''Super Tuesday'' voting, spokesman Karen Hughes said
Saturday. She said giving McCain equal time ''changed the nature of
the interview request,'' so the campaign canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said they would understand if we decided not go to
forward, and so that's what we decided to do,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Bush had accepted a longstanding invitation
to appear on the CBS program.
</P>
<P>
   With the Super Tuesday contests so near, CBS came to the
conclusion that devoting a segment to the Texas governor would be
unfair to McCain. Producers approached the Bush camp about
alternatives, but none was acceptable and the interview was
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''With him accepting at that late hour so close to Super
Tuesday, we felt it would be necessary to have Senator McCain
either in the same segment, different interviews on the same show
or some way to give it balance,'' CBS spokesman Kevin Tedesco said.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain campaign aide said the Bush decision was not
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the eve of Super Tuesday, he clearly is not interested in a
free-flowing exchange of ideas on one of the most-watched
television shows in the country,'' said McCain campaign spokesman
Todd Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is he afraid of? It's no accident he's turning this down
as news is breaking on the $2.5 million being dumped into this
campaign by his cronies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 1948 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Victims Enter Camps  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Thousands of Mozambique's hungry and
thirsty flood victims straggled into makeshift camps Saturday after
days of huddling on rooftops or clinging to tree branches.
</P>
<P>
   As more supplies and equipment arrived from around the world --
including the first of three U.S. planes carrying boats from Miami
-- survivors converged on camps.
</P>
<P>
   There they gulped down cornmeal soup and beans, the first food
many had eaten in four or five days. Authorities estimated that 1
million people in this southeast African country urgently require
food, medicine and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials said hunger and thirst had driven some to eat the
carcasses of drowned animals and to drink filthy floodwater,
putting them at risk of cholera, a highly contagious, often lethal
disease. People waiting for emergency help also stood among clouds
of malaria-carrying mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers expected the death toll from the disaster to soar
into the thousands as floodwaters in southern Mozambique receded
and revealed the twisted mud-covered remains of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclone Eline, which along with three weeks of torrential rains
caused the flooding, was downgraded Friday to a tropical storm. On
Saturday, the dazed and dirty survivors, stripped of all their
possessions by the surging water, recounted their ordeals as they
congregated in the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Mareleko spent five days in waist-deep water clinging
with his two wives to a tree. The tree's branches were beyond reach
and the swift current froze them against the trunk so they stood,
unable to sleep, until a South African Air Force helicopter rescued
them Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While they held on for their lives, the bodies of six neighbors
floated past.
</P>
<P>
   Mareleko, waiting in line to register at a camp near the village
of Palmeira, said he had no idea what he would do next. He was
simply thankful he and his immediate family were alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling very happy I survived the water,'' the 24-year-old
farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, clean water was in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   In one camp near Chokwe, there was not enough drinking water for
the 3,500 refugees, the World Food Program said.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport near Mozambique's steamy seaside capital of
Maputo, Charles Monteiro of the Spanish Red Cross was overseeing
the unloading of six water purifiers that together can clean 4,160
gallons an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ''These will be in operation soon,'' Monteiro said as the
equipment descended from the bowels of a massive Antonov cargo
plane. The machines are vital in averting outbreaks of cholera from
contaminated drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby on the airport tarmac, two other Antonovs from Germany
and Belgium were disgorging relief supplies, which smaller planes
and helicopters ferried to outlying regions.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian cargo plane landed in the central city of Beira with
40 tons of relief supplies, and the U.S. planeload of boats arrived
in Maputo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique's National Disaster Coordination Center welcomed the
aid but said more was needed. Authorities stressed that
distribution of the aid needed to be better coordinated to prevent
the relief supplies from piling up at depots or winding up in the
hands of corrupt officials. Officials at the center said some food
relief was already being sold in town markets.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also warned that floodwaters had shifted land mines
left over from Mozambique's civil war, which ended in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a dispute with neighboring South Africa was delaying
the arrival of American and British military relief efforts, the
Saturday Star of Johannesburg reported, quoting unidentified
British diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said the South African government was insisting
that the United States and Britain base their aid operations in
Maputo rather than Hoedspruit air base in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   A Royal Air Force Tristar transport aircraft was being held on
the ground at Hoedspruit and a second Tristar was awaiting
clearance before taking off from Britain, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military aircraft, dispatched by President Clinton to aid
the relief operation, were also delaying their departure for
Africa, pending clearance from the South African government to land
at Hoedspruit, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   London and Washington prefer the superior facilities at
Hoedspruit to those in Mozambique, but Mozambican officials have
said the military relief effort would be better based on their
soil, it said.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Mozambique's high commissioner to Britain on Saturday
criticized the international response to the flood as being too
slow.
</P>
<P>
   ''The delay of response from the international community to come
with relief to the Mozambican people really has caused the loss of
so many lives,'' Eduardo Koloma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
