<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Explains Chechnya in Mideast  </HEADLINE>
By TAREK AL-TABLAWI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- In an attempt to ease Arab anger over its
war against Muslim rebels in Chechnya, Russia has reportedly
invited a delegation from the Arab League to come to the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-member Arab League released a statement Saturday saying
visiting Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov issued the invite.
The statement did not say whether a delegation would go to
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the Arab world sympathize with fellow Muslims in
Chechnya. Several Arab nations have sent aid to the Russian
republic and have urged Moscow to end its military offensive there.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow sent ground forces into Chechnya in September after
Muslim fighters based there invaded the neighboring republic of
Dagestan and after several bombing at apartment buildings blamed on
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov met Saturday with President Hosni Mubarak in the Red Sea
resort of Sharm el-Sheik. Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported
that the talks revolved around the situation in Chechnya and the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In a later meeting with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa,
Ivanov denied that the conflict in Chechnya had hurt Russia's
historically warm relations with the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov blamed the conflict in Chechnya on ''terrorism,'' adding:
''You in Egypt have suffered from this before.'' He was referring
to the Egyptian government's nearly 8-year struggle against Muslim
extremists seeking an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chechen people are victims of this terrorism,'' which is
aided by ''elements that have no relation to Chechnya,'' Ivanov
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, university students protested Ivanov's visit to Egypt
with rallies in Cairo and the Mediterranean coastal city of
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   In demonstrations on two separate campuses of Alexandria
University, students called for Arab unity, shouted anti-Israel
slogans and distributed leaflets saying ''Russian Foreign Minister
... You are not welcome.'' Police maintained a heavy presence just
outside the grounds, but the demonstrations did not spread.
</P>
<P>
   In the Egyptian capital, Cairo University students peacefully
protested Russia's offensive in Chechnya as well as last month's
Israeli air strikes on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In Saudi Arabia, Russian envoy Ramazan Abdulatipov met with
Crown Prince Abdullah. The prince told him the conflict in Chechnya
must stop, and the two sides should negotiate instead of spilling
more Muslim blood, a Saudi foreign ministry official said on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Abdulatipov was expected to meet Sunday with officials at the
Organization of the Islamic Conference to exchange views on the
conflict. The organization, based in the Red Sea port city of
Jiddah, represents 55 Islamic nations.
</P>
<P>
   Charity drives in Saudi Arabia for Chechen refugees have raised
more than $12.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
