<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Attack Israeli Base  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas attacked an Israeli military
outpost in southern Lebanon on Saturday night, wounding an Israeli
soldier and prompting strikes from Israeli warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas fired rockets at the military base at Beaufort, a
centuries-old mountaintop castle 12 miles north of the Israeli
border with commanding views of southern Lebanon and northern
Israel, Lebanese security officials said. Soldiers returned fire
from tanks, and Israeli artillery pounded the surrounding area, the
officials said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded Israeli soldier was evacuated by helicopter to
Israel for treatment, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli security official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the soldier was seriously injured and
being treated at a hospital in the northern Israeli city of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army spokesman's office confirmed an exchange of
fire at the castle and airstrikes nearby.
</P>
<P>
   No further information was available on the casualties or
exchanges, which lasted more than an hour. None of the guerrilla
groups active in southern Lebanon immediately claimed
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   About 1{ hours after the attack, Israeli warplanes struck an
area southwest of the castle, firing at least one missile. Two
missiles were fired in a second airstrike 20 minutes later,
security officials said. The planes were believed to be pursuing
the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas have killed seven Israeli
soldiers and six pro-Israeli militiamen, including the South
Lebanon Army militia's No. 2 commander, since Jan. 25. The
escalation in violence prompted Israeli warplanes to bomb three
power stations deep inside Lebanon on Feb. 8, wounding 15 civilians
and causing widespread power outages.
</P>
<P>
   Israel set up the zone it occupies in southern Lebanon in 1985
to protect its northern communities from cross-border guerrilla
raids. The border strip, 10 percent of Lebanon's territory, is
patrolled by 1,500 Israeli soldiers and 2,500 allied South Lebanon
Army militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who has set a July deadline
for the withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern Lebanon, has
pledged even harsher retaliation if attacks continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
