<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Skips TV Show Due to McCain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- George W. Bush scrapped a planned interview
on Sunday's ''60 Minutes'' after his Republican presidential rival,
Sen. John McCain, was offered equal time by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides say they contacted the show to suggest a
debate or at least get equal time for their candidate. A CBS
official says the network was interested in offering McCain a
chance to appear on the show anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign had viewed the interview as ''a good
opportunity to speak to a lot of people'' before Tuesday's
13-state, ''Super Tuesday'' voting, spokesman Karen Hughes said
Saturday. She said giving McCain equal time ''changed the nature of
the interview request,'' so the campaign canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said they would understand if we decided not go to
forward, and so that's what we decided to do,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Bush had accepted a longstanding invitation
to appear on the CBS program.
</P>
<P>
   With the Super Tuesday contests so near, CBS came to the
conclusion that devoting a segment to the Texas governor would be
unfair to McCain. Producers approached the Bush camp about
alternatives, but none was acceptable and the interview was
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''With him accepting at that late hour so close to Super
Tuesday, we felt it would be necessary to have Senator McCain
either in the same segment, different interviews on the same show
or some way to give it balance,'' CBS spokesman Kevin Tedesco said.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain campaign aide said the Bush decision was not
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the eve of Super Tuesday, he clearly is not interested in a
free-flowing exchange of ideas on one of the most-watched
television shows in the country,'' said McCain campaign spokesman
Todd Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is he afraid of? It's no accident he's turning this down
as news is breaking on the $2.5 million being dumped into this
campaign by his cronies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
