<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Take on Northeast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- Presidential hopefuls John McCain and George W. Bush
were back on the campaign trail in the Northeast region today, hoping to sway
voters before the ''Super Tuesday'' primary on March 7. Accompanied by New York
Gov. George Pataki and a host of New York congressmen, Bush spoke about
education policy as he visited Rochester and Binghamton in a quest for the
state's 101 convention delegates. Polls show McCain leading Bush in some New
England states, so the Arizona senator started his day in Boston before flying
to an event in Portland, Maine. Polls indicate a tight race in New York and
McCain was also making stops in Syracuse and Rochester.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Explains Chechnya in Mideast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- In an attempt to ease Arab anger over its war against
Muslim rebels in Chechnya, Russia has reportedly invited a delegation from the
Arab League to come to the breakaway republic. The 22-member Arab League
released a statement Saturday saying visiting Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov issued the invite. The statement did not say whether a delegation would
go to Chechnya. Many people in the Arab world sympathize with fellow Muslims in
Chechnya. Several Arab nations have sent aid to the Russian republic and have
urged Moscow to end its military offensive there.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Rally Held in Ala.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Confederate flags and rebel yells rose from the
steps of Alabama's Capital today as a group that wants the South to secede from
the union staged a Confederate flag-waving rally. Afterward, members of the
Southern nationalist organization that organized the event signed a
''Declaration of Southern Cultural Independence,'' described as the first step
in what they hope is a second secession by the South. Montgomery police and Hill
estimated the crowd at about 2,500.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yemen Releases Polish Ambassador
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Yemeni tribesmen released the Polish ambassador unharmed
early Sunday after holding him captive for nearly four days. Krzysztof Suprowicz
arrived Sunday morning at the embassy in the capital San'a, his wife Nina said.
Suprowicz was abducted Wednesday by members of the Yamaneyatain tribe after
dropping his wife and daughter off at the dentist in downtown San'a. The
abductors were demanding the Yemeni government free fellow tribesmen arrested
recently in exchange for the diplomat's release. The ambassador's release
followed a day of roller-coaster negotiations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley Invokes Truman During Speech
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An upbeat Bill Bradley brushed aside long odds facing his
campaign today and spoke of ''a world of possibilities guided by goodness,''
reminding his volunteers that another Missouri native, Harry Truman, defied the
polls to win an election more than 50 years ago. Bradley was accompanied by
former New York City Mayor Ed Koch and actor Harvey Keitel when he met in
Greenwich Village with volunteers. He and his wife, Ernestine, also were holding
a rally on New York's Upper West Side before heading to a ''Democrat Days''
event in Hannibal, Mo.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lockerbie Prosecutor: Trial Is On
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. (AP) -- Scotland's top prosecutor met today with the families
of the victims of the Lockerbie jet bombing to assure them the case was going to
trial, despite the sudden resignation of his predecessor. The trial is set to
begin May 3 in the Netherlands under Scottish law. Libyans Abdel Basset Ali
al-Magrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhiman face charges including murder and conspiracy
to murder in the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103. The plane exploded over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, killing 259 passengers and 11 people on
the ground.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Houston Honored by Soul Train
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Whitney Houston and the artist formerly known as Prince
were singled out for ''artist of the decade'' awards at the Soul Train Music
Awards presented today. Houston distinguished herself in the 1990s with millions
of CD sales, while co-starring in movies ''The Bodyguard,'' ''The Preacher's
Wife,'' and the television special ''Cinderella.'' The artist formerly known as
Prince, who changed his name to an unpronounceable symbol, was singled out for
his leadership during the decade for pioneering a concept of Internet
distribution of CD releases by artists attached to his record label.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UCLA Upsets No. 1 Stanford 94-93 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- JaRon Rush, playing his first game after a nine-game
suspension, hit a disputed baseline jumper with 3 seconds remaining in overtime
as UCLA upset No. 1 Stanford 94-93 today. Rush, who scored 19 points to lead the
Bruins, grabbed a loose ball under the UCLA basket after a wild scrum during
which the shot clock appeared to expire. Stanford's Casey Jacobsen then missed a
desperate half-court shot, and UCLA ran to its locker room in celebration.
</P>
