<HEADLINE> Balloonist Expected Home Next Week  </HEADLINE>
By KATE N. GROSSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- After resting overnight in a hospital in the
Asian nation of Myanmar, balloonist Kevin Uliassi spent Saturday
packing up his 160-foot balloon and capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Uliassi on Friday abandoned his attempt to become the first solo
balloonist to circle the globe, 10 days after lifting off from a
stone quarry outside Rockford in northern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   He landed his balloon safely in a field in central Myanmar,
formerly known as Burma, after traveling more than 13,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't injured, except for a few bruises, flight spokesman
Scott Lorenz said. He expects Uliassi to return to the United
States sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the location Uliassi chose for landing is near
the only ballooning port in Southeast Asia, Lorenz said. Cary
Crawley, a pilot at the ballooning station, helped UIiassi pack up
the balloon, which was described as being in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   Because of limited communications since the landing, the ground
crew still does not know why Uliassi ended the flight, Lorenz said.
They believe he had enough fuel, food and oxygen to complete the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Uliassi said her husband should have no regrets about
failing to circle the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ''This project was a success for us,'' she said Saturday. ''As
two individuals -- like the common man out there -- we were able to
pull together a balloon that could fly around the world. And Kevin
got a trip of a lifetime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
