<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families of Lockerbie victims have tough questions for newprosecutor  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new chief prosecutor in the Pam Am Flight 103 bombing case
arrived in the U.S. Saturday to reassure families of the victims
that the case against two suspects remains on track.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Lord Advocate Colin Boyd met with families and U.S.
officials near Boston, and has scheduled another meeting Monday in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Monetti, 57, of Cherry Hill, N.J., listened to Boyd's
assurances, but said the sudden resignation of Boyd's predecessor
was another blow to the families.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd took over the case following the unexpected resignation of
former Lord Advocate Andrew Hardie last month. It was the latest in
a series of indications raising doubts as to whether the
prosecution's case is as straightforward or watertight as U.S. and
British authorities have asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need the agony, and the trial is going to be long
enough as it is,'' said Monetti, whose 20-year-old son, Rick, died
on the plane. ''I wish it was half over already.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd can expect more tough questions from families at Monday's
meeting, according to the parents of another New Jersey victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can reassure to his heart's content, but we still have lots
of questions,'' said Susan Cohen of Cape May Court House, whose
20-year-old daughter, Theodora, was among 38 New Jerseyans killed
when the Pan Am jet exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland on Dec. 21,
1988.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion killed 259 passengers and crew -- including 189
Americans -- and 11 people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyan suspects are to stand trial for the bombing in May,
but Cohen said she considers the trial a farce that fails to
address the central question of who ordered the bombing. Her
husband, Daniel, plans to attend Monday's meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can assure you (Boyd) is not going to have an easy time in
Washington,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen said she is sure a deal was cut with Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi that prompted him to turn Abdel Basset Ali
al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah over to prosecutors last year
to stand trial at Camp Zeist, a former U.S. air base in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I consider this trial little more than political theater,''
she said Saturday. Using the analogy of a mob trial, she said the
prosecution fails to go high enough up the chain of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a conspiracy case; (the suspects) are just the hit men
for the head of the Mafia. The guy who's the head of the Mafia is
protected before the trial starts. If you made that kind of a deal
in this country, it would be quite a scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cohen said someone -- whom she would not identify -- read her
and other victims' families excerpts from a letter purporting to be
from United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to Gadhafi last
February. The deferential tone of the letter, with references to
not wanting to undermine Gadhafi's regime, led her to believe
private assurances were made to the Libyan leader about what would
and would not be discussed at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only reason Gadhafi turned these two over is because
negotiations occurred,'' she said. ''I call this the Gadhafi
protection trial. I'm not accusing the Lord Advocate of suppression
of evidence, but the deal is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said Saturday he wouldn't object to the release of the
Annan letter, though he pointed out he has no authority to release
the document, which is in the hands of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintain that the two Libyan suspects were
responsible for placing a suitcase bomb on a flight originating in
Malta and having it transferred onto the Pan Am airliner in London.
The men, employed by the Libyan national airline in Malta, were
allegedly undercover intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, Scottish legal sources reported that a star
witness had backpedalled on his earlier account that he saw one of
the men place the suitcase on the conveyor belt in Malta.
</P>
<P>
   An investigative report in the Scottish Sunday Herald last month
claimed Hardie resigned ''because he realized that the Lockerbie
case was a shambles and would probably end in acquittal for the two
Libyan defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The case,'' it said, ''is plagued with problems including
witnesses changing statements, allegations that original FBI
witness statements no longer tally with witnesses' current account
of events and new witnesses coming forward who will throw the whole
concept of a Libyan plot into disarray.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardie dismissed the reports, and said if he had doubts about
the strength of the case, he would have ended the prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
