<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Republicans Spar for Primary Votes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- The race for the Republican presidential nomination
picked up speed this weekend as Texas Governor George W. Bush and Arizona
Senator John McCain made stops throughout the Northeast region. Bush made
campaign stops in New York state in a quest for the state's 101 convention
delegates. Polls show McCain leading Bush in some New England states, so the
Arizona senator started his day in Boston before flying to an event in Portland,
Maine. Polls indicate a tight race in New York and McCain was also making stops
in Syracuse and Rochester.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Camps Welcome Mozambique Flood Victims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Thousands of Mozambique flood survivors ate
their first meal in four or five days today in makeshift camps as supplies and
equipment arrived from around the world. Mozambique's National Disaster
Coordination Center welcomed the aid but said more was needed. Authorities
stressed that distribution of the aid needed to be better coordinated to prevent
the relief supplies from piling up at depots or winding up in the hands of
corrupt officials. Aid workers expected the death toll from the disaster to soar
into the thousands as floodwaters in southern Mozambique receded and revealed
the remains of the dead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Disperse Pinochet Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Thousands marched today in Chile demonstrating
against the return of General Augusto Pinochet, and police opened water cannons
to disperse the protesters. Pinochet, 84, returned home Friday after 503 days
under house arrest in Britain. He had been held on a warrant by a Spanish judge
who wanted to extradite him and try him for human rights abuses during his
1973-90 dictatorship in Chile. His return -- and the fact that he dodged trial
abroad for his alleged crimes -- have exacerbated the tensions here.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Explains Chechnya in Mideast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- In an attempt to ease Arab anger over its war against
Muslim rebels in Chechnya, Russia has reportedly invited a delegation from the
Arab League to come to the breakaway republic. The 22-member Arab League
released a statement Saturday saying visiting Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov issued the invite. The statement did not say whether a delegation would
go to Chechnya. Many people in the Arab world sympathize with fellow Muslims in
Chechnya. Several Arab nations have sent aid to the Russian republic and have
urged Moscow to end its military offensive there.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yemen Frees Polish Ambassador
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- Yemeni tribesmen released the Polish ambassador unharmed
early Sunday after holding him captive for nearly four days. Krzysztof Suprowicz
arrived Sunday morning at the embassy in the capital San'a, his wife, Nina,
said. Suprowicz was abducted Wednesday by members of the Yamaneyatain tribe. The
abductors were demanding the Yemeni government free fellow tribesmen arrested
recently in exchange for the diplomat's release. The ambassador's release
followed a day of roller-coaster negotiations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: 600 Falun Gong Leaders Held
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese authorities have arrested at least 600 leading
members of a meditation-exercise sect they outlawed as an ''evil cult,'' similar
to the Falun Gong spiritual movement, a human rights group said. Meanwhile, with
security tight ahead of Sunday's opening of the annual 10-day legislative
session of the National People's Congress, police in Beijing seized at least 10
Falun Gong members who attempted to sit in a meditation pose in Tiananmen
Square. The would-be protesters were quickly dragged off the pavement and put
into waiting vans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Microchip War Heating Up
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Aiming to beat rival Intel Corp. to the starting gate,
Advanced Micro Devices has moved up the launch of its 1-gigahertz computer chip,
the Houston Chronicle reported today. Industry sources told the Chronicle that
the Sunnyvale, Calif., chip maker will begin selling its 1-GHz Athlon on Monday.
Both companies' announcements are ahead of schedule as they race to be first out
with the fastest personal computer chips. Both AMD, based in Sunnyvale, Calif.,
and Intel, of Santa Clara, Calif., had originally said their gigahertz
processors wouldn't be launched until midyear.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UCLA Upsets No. 1 Stanford 94-93 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- JaRon Rush, playing his first game after a nine-game
suspension, hit a baseline jumper with 3 seconds remaining in overtime as UCLA
upset No. 1 Stanford 94-93 today. Rush, who scored 19 points to lead the Bruins,
grabbed a loose ball under the UCLA basket after a wild scrum during which the
shot clock appeared to expire. Stanford's Casey Jacobsen then missed a desperate
half-court shot, and UCLA ran to its locker room in celebration.
</P>
