<HEADLINE> Jewish Group Awards Sultan of Oman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUSCAT, Oman (AP) -- The American Jewish Committee awarded Omani
Sultan Qaboos its Leadership for Peace Award Saturday for promoting
regional peace, the Oman News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Al-Sayed Fahd bin Mahmoud Al Saeed, the deputy prime
minister for Cabinet affairs, received the award on behalf of
Qaboos. The sultan was not expected to meet with committee members
during their visit.
</P>
<P>
   Qaboos was honored by the New York-base group for his
government's efforts toward promoting Middle East peace and also
for trade and investment with the United States, the news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members were also heading to Qatar, where they were
expected to meet with the Qatari leader, or emir, Sheik Hamad bin
Khalifa Al Thani.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gulf countries have had limited official relations with
Israel, though both backed off when Arab-Israeli peace efforts
stalled under the leadership of former Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Oman established commercial ties with Israel in 1995 and opened
a trade mission in Tel Aviv. But it froze relations with the Jewish
state two years later, under Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Qatar has no diplomatic relations with Israel, but established
trade ties in 1995. The following year, then-Prime Minister Shimon
Peres became the only Israeli leader to visit Qatar. The trade
ties, however, were frozen after Netanyahu's election later in
1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
