<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
Essie Edmiston:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Essie Green Edmiston, an art dealer who
represented many 20th century black artists through her Harlem
gallery, died Feb. 26 of bladder cancer. She was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Edmiston began showing art in her Brooklyn apartment in the
1970s, while running a full-time psychiatric social work practice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 she focused on art, establishing the Park Plaza Gallery
in the Park Slope section of Brooklyn, and a decade later, the
Essie Green Galleries in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   There she showed work by Romare Bearden, Lois Mailou Jones and
Jacob Lawrence, all of whom she knew as friends. She also showed
the work of Allen Stringfellow, Norman Lewis, William S. Carter,
William Ossawa Tanner, Charles Ethan Porter, Edwin Bannister and
Charles Alston.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s she organized shows of Bearden and Stringfellow at
the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Edmiston was a founding stockholder of the Innercity
Broadcasting Corporation, which owns the radio stations WBLS-FM and
WLIB-AM in New York City. She was also a board member of the
Nanette Bearden Contemporary Dance Theater.
Geeta Mukherjee:
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Geeta Mukherjee, a veteran leader of the
Communist Party of India, died Saturday of a heart attack,
officials of her party said. She was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Mukherjee was preparing to leave for a party program in the
northern town of Aligarh, 75 miles southeast of the capital, New
Delhi, when she was stricken, the Press Trust of India news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mukherjee, the widow of prominent communist party leader
Bishwanath Mukherjee, was one of the founding members of the
communist movement in the state of West Bengal.
</P>
<P>
   She also was secretary of the party's national council and its
deputy leader in the Lok Sabha, India's lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Mukherjee was deeply involved with women's issues, spearheading
the communists' demand for setting aside a third of all seats in
parliament and state legislatures for women.
Charles Wiggins
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Federal appeals court Judge Charles Wiggins,
who as a California congressman in the 1970s was among President
Nixon's staunchest defenders before urging him to resign, died
Thursday of cardiac arrest. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins was appointed in 1984 by President Reagan to the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco. He had been a
senior judge on the court and lived in Las Vegas for the last 3{
years.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins, a Republican from the Southern California district once
represented by Nixon, served in the House from 1967 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He was considered Nixon's strongest defender on the House
Judiciary Committee during the Watergate hearings in 1974. He later
switched positions and called for Nixon's resignation or
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of the respected congressman was regarded as a key
factor in the final erosion of Nixon's support on Capitol Hill and
Nixon's decision to resign.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1974, after Nixon acknowledged lying about his role in
the Watergate coverup, Wiggins announced he was ready to vote for
impeachment on Article 1, alleging obstruction of justice. Three
days later, Nixon resigned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley invokes long-shot Harry Truman in valedictory weekend  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An upbeat Bill Bradley brushed aside long odds
facing his campaign Saturday and spoke of ''a world of
possibilities guided by goodness,'' reminding his volunteers that
another Missouri native, Harry Truman, defied the polls to win an
election more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley entered the final weekend before Super Tuesday behind in
the delegate count, trailing in polls and no longer considered a
threat to Democratic presidential rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know Harry Truman. They said he was finished in 1948, he
didn't have a chance,'' Bradley told volunteers in Greenwich
Village, who were preparing to canvass door to door. ''And you know
what happened there. He came from behind and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether by accident or by design, Bradley campaigned Saturday in
two states crucial to his life story -- Missouri, where he was born
and raised, and New York, where he became a professional basketball
star with the Knicks and learned both how to win and how to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was accompanied by former New York City Mayor Ed Koch
and actor Harvey Keitel when he met in Greenwich Village with
volunteers. He and his wife, Ernestine, also were holding a rally
on New York's Upper West Side before heading to a ''Democrat Days''
event in Hannibal, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, meanwhile, campaigned in clear-sailing
style in Massachusetts and New York. He dropped by Charlie's
Sandwich Shoppe in Boston for blueberry pancakes, escorted by Mayor
Thomas M. Menino and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, who called Gore ''Mr.
Strong Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pecora, a Massachusetts state worker who said he
historically votes Republican, offered this observation: ''Bradley
doesn't have a shot. He doesn't seem to be competing with Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   All references to Bradley long gone from Gore's speeches, he
turned his fire on Republican presidential contenders John McCain
and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by state officials and wrapped in sunshine, Gore told
about 2,000 supporters outside Faneuil Hall that Tuesday's votes in
15 states ''will be the decisive moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republican candidates go into private meetings -- one of
them with Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson -- and they come out and
Falwell and Robertson pat them on the back and say 'we heard
everything we wanted to hear,''' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me break that code for you. What they're saying is they
heard a solemn promise to give the right-wing extremist wing of the
Republican Party control of our Supreme Court and the
interpretation of our Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times endorsed Gore in Sunday editions saying he
has ''a burning desire to step out of his mentor's shadow and prove
that he possesses the self control and presidential high-mindedness
so lacking in Mr. Clinton.'' The Kansas City Star and the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch endorsed Bradley in weekend editions.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Dispatch declared: ''Mr. Bradley lacks charisma but not
sincerity.'' In its editorial, The Star said Bradley ''can offer
fresh perspectives and can champion the party's best ideals without
the baggage that Gore must carry.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Gore changed into a kelly-green necktie and
promised the Irish-American Presidential Forum he would be
''studying up on'' the complexities of the Northern Ireland peace
process and would make peace there ''one of my causes'' in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Bradley also launched a new direction for his
campaign, unveiling a stump speech criticizing Gore as a political
chameleon. Now Gore's name has disappeared from his speeches, and
Bradley is talking about ideas again and staking his survival on a
strong showing in New York and New England states in Tuesday's
string of primaries, although he's far behind in the polls in every
state.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'll quit, Bradley smiles, ''One thing we know about
polls is they close very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bradley pep rallies, however, introductions have taken on a
valedictory feel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator Bradley has brought some ideas to the table,'' Ben
Waxman, a Bradley volunteer, told students at Portland High School
in Maine. ''They are the best. They are the biggest. They are the
most daring.''
</P>
<P>
   And campaign post-mortems have begun.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign supporters in the Northeast, Bradley's strongest
region, wondered aloud when Bradley spent six days in Washington
state in advance of a Feb. 29 ''beauty contest'' primary that did
not assign delegates to the Democratic convention. To make matters
worse, Gore trounced Bradley there.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters have also expressed regrets that Bradley opted to
challenge Gore aggressively in the Iowa caucuses, hoping for a
January ''surprise,'' rather than stay focused on winning New
Hampshire. Gore won easily in Iowa and beat Bradley again by a
narrow margin in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, there is envy and disappointment that
McCain, Bradley's counterpart underdog on the GOP side, grabbed so
much press attention and support of independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not that I'm whining,'' said Gale Kaufman, a senior advisor to
the Bradley campaign in California, but the campaign ''fell off the
map'' once the press became fascinated with the McCain insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and his traveling core of advisors remain locked in the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's theme song, played at most rallies, is ''Right
Here, Right Now.'' On the occasions when Bradley does look back, he
invokes history to explain his ''think big'' approach to child
poverty and health care, holding up Franklin Delano Roosevelt and
Thomas Jefferson as examples.
</P>
<P>
   After rallies, Bradley fans mill about, Bradley campaign
stickers affixed to their jackets, describing their feelings of
inspiration tinged with disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think his best position is to provoke thought, and he's done
that,'' said Judith Lessler of Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 2125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Former Coke Workers Rally  </HEADLINE>
By ERIN McCLAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Hundreds of black former Coca-Cola employees
rallied Saturday, calling the company's massive job cuts ''ethnic
cleansing'' and accusing the soft-drink giant of severely
mistreating workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blacks in the company are humiliated, intimidated, yelled at,
called the N-word, treated with disrespect,'' said Larry Jones, a
former Coke manager who organized a meeting of about 500 laid-off
black workers Saturday at a church outside Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the real thing,'' he said, mocking a company slogan.
''This is the real Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Ben Deutsch called the allegations of racial
discrimination in the job cuts ''outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The decisions we're making are being done for business
purposes only,'' he said Saturday night. ''We are trying to do
everything we can during this extremely difficult time to do the
right thing for our current and former employees at every turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters applauded Coca-Cola's decision not to require
laid-off workers to sign a waiver forcing them to choose between
participating in a discrimination lawsuit pending against the
company or enjoying better severance benefits. But the workers said
a future boycott of Coca-Cola by black leaders remained an option.
</P>
<P>
   The waiver had left black workers with a difficult decision
because of a racial discrimination suit filed last year by current
and former black employees.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is reducing its worldwide work force by 6,000, with 2,500
of the eliminated jobs coming from its Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in the lawsuit contend that Jones, a black human
resources manager, was laid off Feb. 15 after meeting with Coke
President Jack Stahl to express black employees' concerns about job
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened on Feb. 15 was essentially ethnic cleansing,''
Jones said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Ben Deutsch has said Jones' dismissal was
unrelated to his meeting with Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   The workers demanded Saturday that Coke work harder to settle
the lawsuit, develop a fairer system of employee evaluation and
''stop looking at the price of the stock'' to pay more attention to
diversity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Marijuana Called 'a Crock'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- White House drug czar Barry McCaffrey
spoke harshly against the medical use of marijuana, calling much of
it ''a crock'' and saying more research is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ask a doctor if he really wants a big blunt stuck in a
patient's face as treatment,'' McCaffrey said on Friday, the final
day of a national conference on addiction at the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library and Museum. ''A lot of this is a crock.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 medical marijuana supporters protested outside the
library, carrying signs, banners and a pot plant.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana is banned by the federal government, although voters
in six states -- Alaska, Arizona, California, Maine, Oregon and
Washington -- have approved laws allowing the drug to be used for
medical purposes.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey -- a longtime opponent of medical marijuana use and
other forms of drug legalization -- said the federal government is
spending increasing sums to fight substance abuse, and suggested
state and local governments need to do more to ensure the money is
well-spent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain battle anew in final weekend before Super Tuesday  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- George W. Bush charged John McCain with
''clouded'' education views Saturday and the senator asked
''Where's the outrage?'' over a late surge of money to pay for
negative TV ads, as the two Republicans battled for the vote on
Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's question about ''outrage'' mimicked a line from the
1996 presidential campaign of Bob Dole, a close friend of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In the weekend before Tuesday's 13-state sweepstakes, Bush
campaigned in New York while McCain started in New England, the
geography highlighting the presidential contenders' different
strategies as they seek their share of the 613 delegates up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by New York Gov. George Pataki, the state's
Republican party chairman and a host of New York congressmen, Bush
spoke about education policy as he visited Rochester and Binghamton
in a quest for the state's 101 convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   That bounty is second only to the 162 at stake in California,
where Bush leads McCain among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show McCain leading Bush in some New England states, so
the Arizona senator started his day in Boston before flying to an
event in Portland, Maine. Polls indicate a tight race in New York
and McCain was also making stops in Syracuse and Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby/Reuters/MSNBC poll released Saturday indicated 44.6
percent of New York voters favored Bush while 38.6 percent
supported McCain, with a margin of error of 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Pataki has put his organization -- and his political
capital -- behind the candidacy of Bush, an effort made
unsuccessfully by Michigan Gov. John Engler in his own state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pataki has a real risk of being Englerized,'' said Nelson
Warfield, a Republican operative who helped run Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign and who knows New York politics well. ''If he
is seen as losing his state for Bush, that hurts him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pataki has had trouble keeping the New York troops in
line, with Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari and U.S.
Rep. Peter King switching to McCain from the Bush camp.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday editions, The New York Times endorsed McCain as a
candidate ''who has the potential to prolong a healthy battle for
the soul of the GOP.'' The New York Daily News also endorsed McCain
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush has ''received
a number of endorsements from newspapers all over America,
including some of the newspapers that know him best, such as the
Austin American-Statesman in his hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush later traveled to Hartford, Ct., where he was greeted by
three governors -- John Rowland of Connecticut, Paul Cellucci of
Massachusetts and Christie Todd Whitman of New Jersey, who had
withheld an endorsement while New Jersey publisher Steve Forbes was
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's conservative philosophy ''transcends the litmus test,''
Whitman said, adding, ''we need somebody who will unite us through
our strength, not divide us because of our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides also have their eye on California, where he's been
20 points behind among Republicans in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the theme of a new campaign ad airing in New York and
California, Bush charged that McCain offered a ''clouded vision''
on education policy when asked during a debate Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, Arizona's superintendent of public
education, said McCain has a strong record on supporting state
education efforts, but believes that states must be responsible for
academic standards and testing.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the education ad will run concurrently with a
controversial ad that accused McCain of being opposed to breast
cancer research
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has been running the breast cancer ad arguing
that McCain voted against research on the disease, while McCain
says he has repeatedly voted to boost breast cancer research
spending. The vote cited in the Bush ad was one where McCain
opposed putting breast cancer money in a military spending measure.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's campaign staff called a news conference Saturday
in Southern California with survivors of the disease. California
Assemblywoman Marilyn Brewer, R-Newport Beach, joined the survivors
and their relatives in decrying Bush's use of the subject as a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I take it as a huge offense'' that Bush would try to make
political hay out of McCain's voting record on the subject, said
LaVerne Friedmann, an Irvine, Calif., breast cancer survivor who
had a double mastectomy four years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, two Texas brothers and prominent Bush
supporters, Sam and Charles Wyly, were spending $2.5 million on ads
attacking McCain's environmental record, but Bush denied any
connection or prior knowledge of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   On his way to a rally in Syracuse, N.Y., McCain again referred
to the infusion of money from outside sources. ''It's disgraceful
and shameful conduct and he should tell them to stop,'' McCain
said. ''This is one of the great scandals of American political
history.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain later said Bush campaign was ''doing the same kinds of
things Bill Clinton would do.'' When McCain compared him to Clinton
in a South Carolina television ad, Bush complained that ''was the
lowest blow'' one could give to a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to spend the night Saturday in Austin, Texas,
before returning to California on Sunday. McCain was also heading
to California on Sunday after making stops in Ohio, another Super
Tuesday state.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters aboard his ''Straight Talk Express''
bus, McCain conceded this campaign was probably his last shot at
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ours is a campaign of reform,'' McCain said. ''If we can't
sell the message this time, I'm not sure we can generate that kind
of interest and enthusiasm again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-04-00 2132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
