<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Flood Victims Flock to Camps
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Victims of the massive Mozambique floods found
refuge in makeshift camps Saturday, gulping down meals after being stranded for
days in trees and on rooftops. Mozambique's National Disaster Coordination
Center welcomed the aid but said more was needed. Aid workers expected the death
toll from the disaster to soar into the thousands as floodwaters in southern
Mozambique receded and revealed the remains of the dead. Cyclone Eline, which
along with three weeks of torrential rains caused the flooding, was downgraded
Friday to a tropical storm.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New York Times Endorses Gore, McCain
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times has endorsed Vice President Al Gore and
Arizona Sen. John McCain for Tuesday's upcoming state primary on Super Tuesday.
The Times, which has not endorsed candidates for the presidential primaries
since 1992, will publish the announcement in Sunday edition's op-ed page,
according to a press release today. The release said the endorsements were made
because of the competitiveness of the contests and as a ''tribute to the vigor
and seriousness that the four candidates have brought to this campaign season.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Guerrillas Attack Israeli Base
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas attacked an Israeli military outpost in
southern Lebanon on Saturday night, wounding an Israeli soldier and prompting
strikes from Israeli warplanes. The guerrillas fired rockets at the military
base at Beaufort, a centuries-old mountaintop castle 12 miles north of the
Israeli border with commanding views of southern Lebanon and northern Israel,
officials said. Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas have killed seven Israeli
soldiers and six pro-Israeli militiamen, including the South Lebanon Army
militia's No. 2 commander, since Jan. 25.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Disperse Pinochet Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Thousands marched today in Chile demonstrating
against the return of General Augusto Pinochet, and police opened water cannons
to disperse the protesters. Pinochet, 84, returned home Friday after 503 days
under house arrest in Britain. He had been held on a warrant by a Spanish judge
who wanted to extradite him and try him for human rights abuses during his
1973-90 dictatorship in Chile. His return -- and the fact that he dodged trial
abroad for his alleged crimes -- have exacerbated the tensions here.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Black Former Coke Workers Rally
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Hundreds of black former Coca-Cola employees rallied today,
calling the company's massive job cuts ''ethnic cleansing'' and accusing the
soft-drink giant of severely mistreating workers. Coke spokesman Ben Deutsch
called the allegations of racial discrimination in the job cuts ''outrageous.''
Protesters applauded Coca-Cola's decision not to require laid-off workers to
sign a waiver forcing them to choose between participating in a discrimination
lawsuit pending against the company or enjoying better severance benefits. But
the workers said a future boycott of Coca-Cola by black leaders remained an
option.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chinese Congressman Investigated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A leader of China's national legislature is under
investigation for alleged economic crimes, the government said Saturday.
National People's Congress Vice Chairman Cheng Kejie was not re-elected to the
presidium of the legislature this year because he is suspected of having broken
the law, legislative spokesman Zeng Jianhui told reporters. Cheng is now
''reflecting on his own problems'' and had asked for a leave from the congress,
Zeng said. Cheng's case and that of a former deputy governor of Jiangxi province
are just two of a slew of high-level corruption cases that have undermined
popular support for the Communist Party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kings Beat Spurs 108-103, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Chris Webber scored 31 points and Jon Barry hit two
3-pointers in overtime to lead the Sacramento Kings to a 108-103 victory over
the San Antonio Spurs today. Barry scored eight points in the extra period for
the Kings, who won for the second time in their last seven. David Robinson had
23 points, and Tim Duncan returned after a four-game absence with a lower
abdominal strain and had 22 points for the Spurs, who played in front of a
season-high 35,113 at the Alamodome.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
76ers Beat Bulls 95-84
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Less than three weeks after he was traded to Philadelphia,
Toni Kukoc made his first trip back to Chicago today scoring 11 points with five
assists and rebounds as the 76ers beat the Bulls 95-84. Allen Iverson, playing
with a sore right rotator cuff, led the 76ers with 29 points. Theo Ratliff added
21 points and Eric Snow had 14 rebounds. Ron Artest, guarded by Kukoc most of
the night, led the Bulls with 18, and Matt Maloney added 17 on 4-of-6 shooting,
including 3 of 4 from 3-point range.
</P>
