<DOCNO> APW20000304.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 10 Iowa St. 75, Baylor 54  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- Keep the nets. No. 10 Iowa State will instead
take the outright Big 12 Conference regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Fizer scored 34 points Saturday night as the Cyclones
(26-4, 14-2 Big 12) won 75-54 at Baylor, only to be denied by the
home team the opportunity to cut down the nets in celebration of
their first conference title since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the crown jewel,'' said Iowa State coach Larry
Eustachy, who did not address the net-cutting issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won the title outright. ... We didn't have to share it with
anybody. The hardest part is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State led from start to finish after Fizer scored his
team's first 10 points, eight before Baylor made a basket. Fizer,
the Big 12 scoring leader, has scored 30 points in four of the last
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's only a handful of games left. I just go out there with
the mentality that every time I get the ball and I've got a good
shot, I'm aiming to knock the shot down,'' Fizer said. ''I came out
with the mentality that we were going to win this game. My
teammates got the ball in great places.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones have already set a school record for victories.
They have won 11 more games than last season, the biggest increase
from one season to the next in school history.
</P>
<P>
   When Baylor (13-14, 4-12) battled to 43-40 midway through the
second half, Iowa State responded with nine straight points,
including Fizer's floater in the lane. Stevie Johnson's follow shot
started the run, and Michael Nurse's long 3-pointer pushed the
Cyclones ahead 52-40 with just under 10 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State is seeded No. 1 and gets a first-day bye in next
week's Big 12 tournament. Baylor is the No. 9 seed, and would face
the Cyclones again Friday if its beats Nebraska in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   After Fizer made two free throws to give Iowa State a 41-30 lead
with 17:38 left, Baylor had a 10-2 run to get close. Three players
had follow shots and Tevis Stukes made an underhand scoop during
the six-minute stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears, who had 20 turnovers and shot just 37 percent
(19-of-52), couldn't avoid the inevitable. Baylor has lost all
eight games this season against ranked Big 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''We battled back and then we missed dunks, we didn't block out
and we had poor shots,'' Baylor coach Dave Bliss said. ''We
obviously have shortcomings we try to play around.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukes, a senior playing his last home game, led Baylor with 19
points and fellow senior Jamie Kendrick added 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nurse added 13 points for Iowa State and Kantrail Horton
had 10.
</P>
<P>
   It is still uncertain if Fizer has played his last regular-
season game for Iowa State. He's yet to announce whether he'll
declare early for the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try not to think about the NBA too much. I'm thinking about
finally winning the conference. That was my first goal,'' Fizer
said. ''My next goal is to go far in the Big 12 tournament, and
then to go farther and farther in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now I'm just playing basketball at Iowa State.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
