<DOCNO> APW20000304.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls' John Starks Awaits Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- John Starks swears he's not pouting because he's
still with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Starks, who wants to be waived so he can go to a playoff
contender, sat out his fourth game Saturday because of tendinitis
in his right knee. While coach Tim Floyd said he won't play until a
grievance arbitrator rules on his request, Starks said it all
depends on his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fans don't understand -- can't understand -- what an injury is
until they get inside my body and feel the pain I'm feeling,'' he
said. ''I never sat down on anybody and never will. If I'm able to
go out there and play the way I'm capable of playing, then I'll
step out there on the court. Other than that, I have to wait until
it gets well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulls fans don't seem to care how Starks feels, though. As he
sat on the bench in street clothes during the 95-84 loss to the
Philadelphia 76ers, one fan yelled, ''Hey Starks! Got a uniform
under there?'' A small group chanted, ''Starks' a bum,'' at the end
of the game, and one fan held up a sign that read, ''Hey Starks, No
Cry Babies Allowed!''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not unhappy. I never said I didn't want to be here,''
Starks said. ''I said I want a chance to go to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks, 34, offered to forfeit the rest of his $4 million salary
-- roughly $900,000 -- if the Bulls would waive him, clearing the way
for him to sign with a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks and Miami Heat were interested in adding him
if he won his case, several league sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrator Kenneth Dam ruled Friday that the NBA didn't
circumvent the collective bargaining agreement when it rejected
Starks' request. There is no provision in the collective bargaining
agreement for such a move, the NBA said.
</P>
<P>
   The players union argued that if Starks was willing to give up
his salary, the league shouldn't stand in his way of joining a team
with a shot at a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no circumvention, Dam said a grievance
arbitrator needed to hear the case. Dam is a system arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   Starks' case will go to a grievance arbitrator, with a hearing
expected sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
   While the Starks' saga has the potential to be a distraction for
a team that's already struggling, it hasn't been, Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Potential is a good word. Potentially, it is a distraction,''
he said. ''Up until this point, it has not been a distraction at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Randy Brown agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's hurt. His knees are hurting and he's not prepared to
play,'' Brown said. ''Am I going to question the man's integrity
when he says he's hurt? No.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls can still release Starks and let him sign with another
team, but they'd have to pay the remainder of his salary. Starks
would still be shut out of the playoffs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Players released after 11:59 p.m. on March 1 who then sign with
another team are not eligible to compete in the playoffs. Starks
wanted his release retroactive to Wednesday night to make him
eligible for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand he wants to be with a contender,'' Brown said.
''Who doesn't?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000304.0171 </DOCNO>
