<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czeschin, Byrnes Win at World Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- Tommy Czeschin and Tricia Byrnes
converted near-perfect runs into victories in World Cup halfpipe
events on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Czeschin, of Mammoth Lakes, Calif., picked up his second World
Cup victory with a score of 45.3 points in his first of two runs.
Ross Powers, the 1998 Olympic bronze medalist, was second at 43.6
and Magnus Sterner of Sweden was third at 41.6.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pipe's really good,'' Czeschin said. ''It's a little
small, but it turned out to be a really good pipe. My first run was
solid. I wanted to land smooth and clean so I could go all out on
my second run.''
</P>
<P>
   Czeschin is currently fourth in the World Cup standings behind
Sweden's Thomas Johansson and Fredrick Sterner and Finland's Pasi
Voho. Johansson was hurt in training and missed Saturday's event.
</P>
<P>
   Byrnes, of New Canaan, Conn., won with a 37.8 in her first run,
edging teammate Kim Stacey of Stratton Mountain, Vt., with 37.5
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Sabine Wehr-Hasler, who leads the points race, was
third with a 35.1.
</P>
<P>
   Byrnes' fifth World Cup victory of the year left her in second
place in the season standings behind Wehr-Hasler, with Sweden's
Anna Hellman third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
