<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No.17 Miss St. 62, No.2 Georgia 61  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning
has taken the coaching cliche of one game at a time all the way to
the Southeastern Conference title game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Y'all get bored with what I'm saying. We take it one day at a
time. I don't even know what the game time is tomorrow,'' Fanning
said after her No. 17 Lady Bulldogs beat No. 2 Georgia 62-61 on
Saturday to reach the championship game for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not finished, and we really have to maintain our focus
on just the little things to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs (23-6) will play Tennessee, tied with Georgia
for No. 2 in the AP poll, in the championship game Sunday.
Tennessee beat Vanderbilt 61-53 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nitra Perry scored all 12 of her points in the second half,
including two free throws with 1:42 left to put Mississippi State
ahead to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (29-3) had a chance after Tawana McDonald blocked
Perry's shot with 13 seconds left. Kelly Miller inbounded the ball
with 8.2 seconds left to McDonald, took a return pass and then
clanked a 12-foot jumper off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't do a good job of drawing it,'' Georgia coach Andy
Landers said. ''They didn't do a good job of running it. It wasn't
very effective. It was a total screwup. I'll take credit. I've got
three more years on my contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State, which had trailed by as much as eight in the
second half, rebounded the ball and ran out the final seconds to
end Georgia's 15-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia had been trying to win its first tournament title since
1986 and thought it had the perfect combination with the Miller
twins, Kelly and Coco.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had trouble shooting Saturday, and the twins were
among the worst. Kelly Miller was 5-of-18 for 13 points, Coco
Miller 5-of-12 for 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Landers didn't sound worried about his Lady Bulldogs' first loss
since Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to go home, take the hood off the car and
break the engine down. This is a very good basketball team. I've
lost no confidence in them. If anything we have a chance to learn a
very valuable lesson,'' Landers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is you may have to play a little bit harder on the
offensive end to get the results that were easier to get earlier
(in the season).''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State, playing its third game in as many days,
looked tired for much of the game and didn't start clicking until
Angela Harris' layup tied it at 51 with 4:56 left. The Lady
Bulldogs took their first lead since late in the first half on a
three-point play by LaToya Thomas with 2:43 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The teams swapped the lead three times with four ties in the
final 4:56. Georgia's luck was summed up when Coco Miller saw a
jumper roll around and fall out down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the SEC's leading scorer, led Mississippi State with 19
points. Perry finished with 12, Cynthia Hall had 12 and Harris 10.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia led by as much as 44-36 at the 8:56 mark on a layup by
Coco Miller. But then Thomas finally wore down senior center Angie
Ball with three quick fouls. She connected on a three-point play
and then made two free throws within the next minute.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald finished with 12 for Georgia, and Angie Ball and Deana
Nolan each had 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-04-00 2241 </TRAILER>
