<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 2 Tennessee 61, Vanderbilt 53  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Michelle Snow hit her first six shots
and finished with 20 points to help No. 2 Tennessee beat Vanderbilt
61-53 Saturday night and reach the Southeastern Conference
tournament title game for a third straight year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols (27-3) will face No. 17 Mississippi State, a 62-61
upset winner over Georgia, which was tied for No. 2 in the country
with Tennessee. The Vols will be trying to win their 10th SEC
tournament championship Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt (20-12) was in the semifinals for the first time
since 1995 when the Commodores won the tournament by beating
instate rival Tennessee. But the Commodores haven't beaten the Lady
Vols since then and had to face them for the third time in 29 days.
</P>
<P>
   Snow took away any hopes of an upset in the opening minutes as
Tennessee won for the 12th straight time in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Snow hit jumpers from all over the court and keyed a 13-2 run
with eight points. Her 3-footer with 13:30 to go made it 15-4, and
Vandy didn't get to within eight until it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which has won more SEC tourney games than any other
school, led 36-23 at halftime and built that to as much as 54-39
with 7:24 to go on a bucket by Semeka Randall.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols survived a nearly four-minute stretch without a
point in the second half when Vandy could only get a one basket
from Zuzi Klimesova. They had a chance to get closer inside the
final five minutes. Jillian Danker hit a jumper to get within 56-46
with 4:43 left and then scored on the next possession only to have
the basket nullified by a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Tamika Catchings added 12 points for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Chantelle Anderson led Vanderbilt with 19 points, and Klimesova
finished with 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
