<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, March 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain, Bush Campaign in New England
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopefuls George W. Bush and
John McCain continued on the campaign trail today in different parts of the
Northeast region. In the weekend before Tuesday's 13-state sweepstakes, Bush
campaigned in New York while McCain started in New England, the geography
highlighting the presidential contenders' different strategies as they seek
their share of the 613 delegates up for grabs. Polls show McCain leading Bush in
some New England states, so the Arizona senator started his day in Boston before
flying to an event in Portland, Maine. Polls indicate a tight race in New York
and McCain was also making stops in Syracuse and Rochester.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Flood Victims Flock to Camps
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALMEIRA, Mozambique (AP) -- Food and medical supplies were a welcome sight
for the victims of Mozambique's floods who flocked to makeshift camps on
Saturday. For many, the meals of cornmeal soups and beans was the first thing
they'd eaten in four or five days after being stranded in trees and rooftops,
waiting for aid. Mozambique's National Disaster Coordination Center welcomed the
aid but said more was needed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New York Times Endorses Gore, McCain
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times has endorsed Vice President Al Gore and
Arizona Sen. John McCain for Tuesday's upcoming state primary on Super Tuesday.
The Times, which has not endorsed candidates for the presidential primaries
since 1992, will publish the announcement in Sunday edition's op-ed page,
according to a press release today. The release said the endorsements were made
because of the competitiveness of the contests and as a ''tribute to the vigor
and seriousness that the four candidates have brought to this campaign season.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China's Premier Makes Taiwan Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China will not ''sit idly by'' and accept Taiwan going its
own way, but hopes the island's leaders and people will accept peaceful
reunification, Premier Zhu Rongji said Sunday in a nationally televised speech.
The mainland and the island of Taiwan have been ruled separately since the end
of the Chinese civil war in 1949. China claims Taiwan as a province that must be
reunited eventually. Zhu, who has guided China's economic development, said
Beijing would push ahead with measures to reform debt-ridden state enterprises,
develop infrastructure and stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Rally Held in Ala.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A group that wants the South to secede from the
union staged a Confederate flag-waving rally today, a day before President
Clinton was to lead marchers across a Selma bridge to mark the 35th anniversary
of ''Bloody Sunday'' in the civil rights movement. Afterward, members of the
Southern nationalist organization that staged the rally signed a ''Declaration
of Southern Cultural Independence,'' described as the first step in what they
hope is a second secession by the South. Montgomery police and Hill estimated
the crowd at about 2,500.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World's Population Getting Fatter
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers reported today that for the first time there
may be as many people overweight as there are underweight. But just because
people are gaining weight does not mean that the world is better fed or
healthier than two decades ago when millions more were starving. The report by
Worldwatch researchers suggests that both underweight and overweight poor people
are victims of malnutrition. Well-off minorities in India, China, Brazil and
some other developing nations are growing fat as the poor go hungry. America and
other wealthier countries have the opposite problem: The richer and
better-educated tend to eat right, while the poor often balloon from a diet of
cheap and fatty fast foods.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
SuperSonics Beat Hawks 93-81
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Gary Payton scored 28 points as the Seattle SuperSonics beat
the Atlanta Hawks 93-81 tonight. Vin Baker added 16 for the Sonics, who had lost
three of their last four. Alan Henderson, Jim Jackson and Bimbo Coles each
scored 11 to lead Atlanta, which has lost three of four and six of its last
nine. Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo, who had more fouls (five) than points (three),
matched his season low in scoring. Isaiah Rider took only three shots and
finished with two points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maple Leafs Beat Canadiens 4-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Maple Leafs turned two mistakes by Montreal
goalie Jeff Hackett into goals and held on to beat the Canadiens 4-3 today. Igor
Korolev, Jonas Hoglund, Steve Thomas and Nik Antropov scored for the Leafs, who
maintained a three-point lead over Ottawa for first place in the NHL's Northeast
Division. Benoit Brunet had two goals and Eric Weinrich scored for the
Canadiens, tied with Buffalo for third place in the Northeast Division.
</P>
