<HEADLINE> Farmworkers Protest In Florida  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SCHNEIDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Three dozen farmworkers, joined by nearly
200 supporters, finished a 15-day march Saturday to the
headquarters of the Florida Fruit and Vegetable Association to
protest the wages and working conditions of tomato pickers.
</P>
<P>
   The 230-mile march from Fort Meyers was only the latest in a
series of actions members of the Coalition of Immokalee Workers
have undertaken in an effort to get Florida's tomato growers to
talk to them. The coalition isn't a union but is seeking some
collective bargaining powers.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, members of the coalition engaged in a work
stoppage and two seasons ago six tomato pickers went on a hunger
strike that gained the attention of former President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we want first is a dialogue with the growers,'' said
Lucas Benitez, a coalition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Added Laura Germino, a march coordinator: ''They're not asking
for overtime. They're not asking for vacation time ... They're
asking for the right to talk to their bosses for a decent wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Florida Fruit and Vegetable Association
refused to meet with the marchers Saturday, saying they're not in a
position to represent the growers on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been told by our membership that it isn't in our
place,'' said Ray Gilmer, communication's director of the growers'
association. ''That's between the workers and their employers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
