<HEADLINE> Soccer's Road to 2002 Cup Begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) -- The long road of qualifying games
for the 2002 World Cup began Saturday with Trinidad and Tobago
routing Netherlands Antilles 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from a record 198 countries are competing for spots in
32-nation showcase in South Korea and Japan. This was the first of
809 qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   In the only other qualifying game Saturday -- also from the
region of North and Central America and the Caribbean -- Honduras
beat visiting Nicaragua 3-0 in San Pedro Sula.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and Tobago and Netherland Antilles play again March 18
in the home-and-home series.
</P>
<P>
   Before a crowd of some 8,000 at Haseley Crawford Stadium, Angus
Eve and Arnold Dwarka had two goals each for Trinidad. Marvin
Andrews opened the scoring on an 18th-minute header.
</P>
<P>
   In San Pedro Sula, Alex Pineda Chacon, Ivan Guerrero and Milton
''Tyson'' Nunez scored for Honduras in the game overshadowed by a
border dispute between Honduras and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 police and soldiers provided security at the stadium
and the city banned the sale of alcoholic beverages to prevent
potential problems. No problems were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
