<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No.21 Okla 59, No.13 Okl St. 56  </HEADLINE>
By OWEN CANFIELD, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) -- Nolan Johnson scored 21 points and held
Desmond Mason without a field goal as No. 21 Oklahoma beat No. 13
Oklahoma State 59-56 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory makes the Sooners (24-5, 12-4 Big 12) the No. 3 seed
in the conference tournament. It also spoiled the final home game
for Oklahoma State's seniors in the final game before Gallagher-Iba
Arena is renovated.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (23-5, 12-4) let a 13-point second-half lead slip
away and as a result will be the fourth seed in the Big 12
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, third in the league with 18.6 points per game, was 0-of-8
from the field and finished with six points. Oklahoma's Eduardo
Najera scored just nine -- none in the final 18{ minutes -- but he
got help from Johnson and Kelley Newton down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   A baseline jumper by Joe Adkins gave Oklahoma State a 50-39 lead
with 8:49 to play. Then Oklahoma made six straight shots and scored
on seven consecutive trips in a 17-2 run that gave the Sooners the
lead for good, 56-52. Newton had two 3-pointers, Johnson hit three
baskets and Hollis Price scored five.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins scored on a backdoor layup with 1:11 remaining to get the
Cowboys within 58-56, but they didn't score again. Johnson made a
free throw with 15.3 seconds remaining for a 59-56 lead, and
Glendon Alexander's 3-point try with two seconds left bounced off
the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Montonati had 15 points and Adkins scored 12 for the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Najera, second in the Big 12 with an 18.9 average, didn't make
his first basket until 3:08 remained before halftime. He converted
a three-point play at that point and added four free throws the
rest of the way. He wound up 2-of-10 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher-Iba Arena, which opened in 1938, will be doubled in
size to about 13,000 when it reopens in December. The Cowboys had
won all 14 of their home games before Saturday, when Oklahoma won
its second straight in Stillwater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
