<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 15 Tulsa 83, SMU 78, 2 OT  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Tony Heard hit a 3-pointer with 0.5 seconds left
to force overtime, then sank two free throws with 2.1 seconds
remaining in the second extra period to give No. 15 Tulsa an 83-78
victory over Southern Methodist on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Heard celebrated the last of his last of 24 points by putting
his right index finger to his mouth, as if to hush the rare sellout
crowd at Moody Coliseum, then killed the final seconds by throwing
the ball into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates mobbed him at midcourt to celebrate the Golden
Hurricane's 27th victory, which tied the school record and gave
them the Western Athletic Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa (27-3, 12-2 WAC) will be the top seed in the league
tournament next weekend. The champion doesn't get an automatic bid
into the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs (21-7, 9-5), who haven't beaten a ranked team in
seven years, could have gone a long way toward their first NCAA bid
since 1993 by beating Tulsa. However, inexperience in big games
showed, as SMU blew a three-point lead in the closing seconds of
regulation and a 1-point lead late in the first overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa star Eric Coley rebounded from a cold, sloppy start to
score five of his seven points in the extra periods.
</P>
<P>
   He set the tone in the second overtime by grabbing the opening
tip after several others dropped it, and turned it into a layup for
a 71-69 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs got within 71-70 but Tulsa scored the next eight
points, all on free throws.
</P>
<P>
   SMU hit some bombs to make it 81-78. Then Heard's final two foul
shots ended it.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Davis led SMU with 23 points and Jeryl Sasser added 15.
Each had 10 rebounds. They also had potential game-costing gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis stole a pass at midcourt with 20 seconds left and the
Mustangs up 63-60. As he went for a layup, he spun away from a
defender and lost the ball out of bounds into the SMU bench. That
led to Heard's 3-pointer from the right corner that forced the
first overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Hurricane scored the first three points in the first
overtime and remained ahead until Damon Hancock's layup with 39.7
seconds left put SMU up 69-68. Brandon Kurtz hit a free throw with
19.1 seconds left to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser could have put SMU ahead, but he missed two free throws
with 13.4 seconds to play. Heard again took the final shot, but he
missed and time expired as the teams fought for the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, which has won seven of eight, beat the Mustangs for the
eighth straight time. Last month, the Golden Hurricane cruised to a
70-59 victory as SMU shot 24 percent and hit just 1-of-18
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs ended the season 13-2 at home, both losses coming
in their last two games.
</P>
